base_text: The Lockheed C-5 Galaxy is a large military transport aircraft that was developed by Lockheed and built by Lockheed-Georgia Co. in the United States. It was designed to provide strategic heavy airlift over intercontinental distances and to carry outsized and overweight loads. The C-5 Galaxy is among the largest military aircraft in the world, and is distinctive for its high T-tail, 25-degree wing sweep, and the four turbofan engines mounted on pylons beneath the wings. It is capable of carrying two Abrams main battle tanks or one Chinook helicopter. Introduced in 1969, the C-5 has been continually updated with new technology and is still in service. It also has the ability to "kneel" down to facilitate loading and unloading cargo. A fully loaded C-5 Galaxy has a maximum weight of 381,000 kilograms. It plays an essential role in providing the US military with logistical flexibility. Its performance and capabilities have made it an integral part of military operations worldwide.
sumy: It is capable of carrying two Abrams main battle tanks or one Chinook helicopter.

base_text: Loch Buie is a small sea loch located on the Southern coast of the Isle of Mull, in the Inner Hebrides of Scotland. Although it is less frequented by tourists than other parts of the Isle of Mull, those who do visit Loch Buie often praise it for its tranquil and scenic beauty. The loch is surrounded by gentle hills leading to rugged mountains in the distance, providing a picturesque view for visitors. Next to Loch Buie is the pretty and historic Moy Castle, which was built in the 15th century by the MacLaine clan. The loch marks the start of an interesting circular walk, taking in remnants of an ancient stone circle, a mausoleum and several Iron Age fortifications. It is also an ideal spot for wildlife watching; you can often see various bird species, seals and occasional sea otters. The surrounding woodland and moorland areas are perfect for quiet contemplation and getting close to nature. It is advised to take a good map and suitable walking shoes as paths can be quite rugged. Despite its remoteness, Loch Buie offers a serene, historic and beautiful Scottish wilderness experience. Loch Buie is a reminder of Scotland's rich past and its magnificent natural beauty.
sumy: It is also an ideal spot for wildlife watching; you can often see various bird species, seals and occasional sea otters.

base_text: "When in Rome 2007" usually refers to a film that was released in the year 2007. This movie is a direct-to-video romantic comedy, starring Mary-Kate Olsen and Ashley Olsen. The plot revolves around two sisters who go to Rome, Italy for a summer job. As an expression "When in Rome, do as the Romans do," the sisters enjoy the Italian culture and lifestyle. The film involves themes of love, adventure, and personal growth within a foreign cultural context. The title "When in Rome" comes from the old proverb suggesting that people should adopt the customs of local inhabitants while visiting a foreign place. The film was directed by Steve Purcell and distributed under Dualstar Entertainment Group. Although critically not very acclaimed, it’s a fond part of the Olsen twins’ filmography, remembered for its picturesque setting. It's a light-hearted, teenage comedy that provides escapism and entertainment to its audience. It is not to be confused with the 2010 film of the same name.
sumy: The plot revolves around two sisters who go to Rome, Italy for a summer job.

base_text:
The Grey-crowned Central American squirrel monkey, also known as the Panamanian squirrel monkey, is a species of small and vibrant primates native to Central America, particularly Panama. Despite their name, they are not actually squirrels, but are called so due to their quick, squirrel-like movements. They are characterized by their grey or white hair, which crowns their head and contrasts sharply with the rest of their fur that is black and orange-red. 

These monkeys are known for their social behavior, typically living in large groups of up to 500 individuals. They communicate through a range of vocalizations and physical movements, allowing them to establish social ranks and warn of predators. They spend the majority of their time in the upper canopy of the rainforest, where they forage for fruits, insects, leaves, and small vertebrates. 

The female Grey-crowned Central American squirrel monkeys usually give birth to a single offspring each year. They are listed as "Least Concern" in terms of conservation but are sensitive to changes in their habitat. Despite this, they remain a crucial part of the Central American ecosystems they inhabit playing a vital role in seed dispersion which contributes to the health and diversity of their rainforest habitat.
sumy: These monkeys are known for their social behavior, typically living in large groups of up to 500 individuals.

base_text: William Penn State Forest is named after the founder of the Province of Pennsylvania, William Penn. It is part of the Pennsylvania State Forest system and is located across several counties in the state. With a focus on natural resource conservation, it provides opportunities for local communities and visitors to engage with natural environments. Spanning thousands of acres, the forest offers a variety of recreational activities such as hiking, biking, picnicking, and wildlife viewing. Additionally, it includes several designated Natural Areas and Wild Areas, with the intent to preserve these regions in their natural state. Forest management practices in this forest are carried out following the methods of sustainable forestry. It also serves as a major source for timber and other forest products. Importantly, the forest provides habitat for numerous species, including those that are rare or threatened. Educational programs are also offered in the forest to raise awareness about the importance of forests and conservation. Thus, the William Penn State Forest is not just a geographical location but an embodiment of sustainable forest management, environmental education, and recreation.
sumy: It also serves as a major source for timber and other forest products.

base_text: The term "2016 Atlantic hurricane season" refers to the period in 2016 during which hurricanes typically form in the Atlantic Ocean. This year was particularly active, with 15 named storms, seven hurricanes, and four major hurricanes. The season officially began on June 1 and ended on November 30, these dates historically cover the period each year when most tropical cyclones form in the Atlantic basin. The strongest storm of the season was Hurricane Matthew, which caused extensive devastation and loss of life in the Caribbean and the southeastern United States. Other notable storms during this season included Hurricanes Otto and Nicole. The season was also noted for the unusual number of storms forming in the eastern part of the Atlantic. Despite the high levels of activity, most storms remained out at sea and did not impact land. However, the season still resulted in significant damage and loss. It was one of the deadliest Atlantic hurricane seasons since 2005. The overall impact of the 2016 Atlantic Hurricane Season was widespread and led to a heightened awareness for hurricane preparedness.
sumy: Other notable storms during this season included Hurricanes Otto and Nicole.

base_text: SpongeBob SquarePants Season 4 is the fourth series of the popular American animated television program, SpongeBob SquarePants. The show began in May 1999 and its fourth season was aired from May 6, 2005, to July 24, 2007. The series follows the escapades of the title character, a yellow sea sponge named SpongeBob, and his various friends in the underwater city of Bikini Bottom. Season 4 contains 20 episodes, each divided into two separate segments. This season marked the return of the show's creator, Stephen Hillenburg, after he left the show during the first season. Some of the most popular episodes from this season include "Fear of a Krabby Patty" and "Have You Seen This Snail?” The season received positive reviews from critics and fans alike. Episodes have a variety of plot lines, often centering around SpongeBob's job at the Krusty Krab, his relationship with his friends, and other aspects of underwater life. The show has been praised for its humor, creativity, and the distinct personality of its title character. Overall, SpongeBob SquarePants Season 4 continued the show’s global popularity and success.
sumy: Some of the most popular episodes from this season include "Fear of a Krabby Patty" and "Have You Seen This Snail?” The season received positive reviews from critics and fans alike.

base_text: Fangoria is an internationally distributed American horror film fan magazine, in publication since 1979. It was initially designed as a fantasy-themed magazine before shifting to more horror-centric content. Over the years, Fangoria has grown to incorporate all aspects of horror cinema, including interviews with filmmakers, detailed film criticism, and behind-the-scenes coverage. It became one of the leading platforms to introduce readers to indie gems and cult classics. Aside from its core magazine, Fangoria expanded its reach into films, comic books, and various media outlets. Fangoria has earned a reputation for its graphic and explicit coverage of horror films, which some view as controversial. Through their exclusives and unique insights, they have cultivated a dedicated fan base. The publication was also known for championing and giving substantial coverage to independent and international horror cinema. Despite going digital in 2008, the magazine struggled to maintain profitability and dropped print editions in 2015. However, as of 2018, Fangoria was purchased and revived as a print publication by Cinestate, continuing its legacy in the horror genre.
sumy: It was initially designed as a fantasy-themed magazine before shifting to more horror-centric content.

base_text: Rufinamide is a medication that is used in the treatment of seizures. It is particularly prescribed for a severe form of epilepsy known as Lennox-Gastaut syndrome. This syndrome, found in children, involves multiple types of seizures. Rufinamide works by stabilizing electrical activity in the brain, thereby controlling the number and severity of the seizures. It is not a cure for epilepsy, but it helps manage the condition. Rufinamide is often used as part of combination therapy, which means it is taken along with other anti-seizure medications. It comes in the form of a tablet or liquid and is usually taken twice a day with food. As with any medication, Rufinamide can cause side effects, so it is important to discuss these with your doctor before starting the treatment. The drug should be taken exactly as prescribed to most effectively control seizures. It is recommended never to stop taking Rufinamide without consulting a doctor, as sudden discontinuation can lead to increased seizures.
sumy: It is particularly prescribed for a severe form of epilepsy known as Lennox-Gastaut syndrome.

base_text: The Tamil language is a Dravidian language primarily spoken in the southern Indian state of Tamil Nadu and in the northeastern region of Sri Lanka. It is one of the oldest surviving classical languages in the world. Spoken by approximately 76 million people worldwide, Tamil enjoys the status of being one of the official languages of India, Sri Lanka and Singapore. It is also recognized as a minority language in Malaysia, Mauritius and South Africa. The language has a rich literary tradition spanning over 2000 years, with a unique writing system that has evolved over time. The Tamil script, derived from the Brahmi script, is used to write the Tamil language. Tamil has multiple dialects depending on the social status, region, and religion of the speakers. Notably, it has a classical form that has been preserved in literature and religious contexts. Moreover, Tamil is often taught in schools and universities across the globe. As a testament to its cultural significance, Tamil was declared a classical language by the Indian government in 2004.
sumy: It is also recognized as a minority language in Malaysia, Mauritius and South Africa.

base_text: Hypaspists were an ancient military unit most well-known for their service in Alexander the Great’s armies. They were elite infantrymen, a type of soldier that Alexander the Great adopted from his father, Philip II of Macedon’s army. The name "Hypaspist" means "shield bearer", indicating their role as protectors and frontline soldiers. Their main job was to guard the flanks of the longer spears during a phalanx formation. Aside from their roles in battle, they also served as a personal bodyguard to Alexander during peacetime. Despite their title suggesting they were light troops, evidence suggests they were probably high-status heavy infantry. They were prominent in significant battles, such as the battles of Issus and Gaugamela. The Hypaspists were later renamed 'Silver Shields' by Seleucus I Nicator, a general under Alexander the Great. This name change emphasized the prestige, seniority, and veteran status of the unit. Today, they are remembered as one of the most successful and formidable military units in history.
sumy: Hypaspists were an ancient military unit most well-known for their service in Alexander the Great’s armies.

base_text: The Turkish invasion of Cyprus, also known as Operation Attila, was a military operation that occurred in July and August of 1974. This happened when Turkish forces invaded the island nation of Cyprus, resulting in a partition of the island that continues today. The invasion was launched in response to a Greek-backed coup attempting to unite Cyprus with Greece, opposing the interests of the island's Turkish Cypriot minority. It began on July 20, 1974, with the Turkish army landing near Kyrenia. This was followed by a second invasion in August, leading to significant territorial gains. The result was a de facto partition of the island into two entities. The northern part, about 36% of the island, was occupied by Turkey which later declared its independence as the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus, recognized only by Turkey. The southern part, internationally recognized as the Republic of Cyprus, is majority Greek Cypriot. The Turkish invasion and the subsequent occupation of Northern Cyprus have been the subject of ongoing geopolitical controversy.
sumy: This happened when Turkish forces invaded the island nation of Cyprus, resulting in a partition of the island that continues today.

base_text: 8701 refers to the numeric title of American R&B singer Usher's third studio album, which was released in 2001. It signifies a change in Usher's musical style from his previous albums towards more matured themes and sophisticated rhythm and blues (R&B). The title, 8701, is a cryptic reference to its release date (2001) and Usher's own career beginnings back in 1987. base_text: The anatomical theatre of the Archiginnasio is a significant historical site located in Bologna, Italy. It is situated inside the Palazzo dell'Archiginnasio, the old seat of the University of Bologna which is one of the world's oldest universities. This theatre is famously known for its unique role as a venue for public dissections during the middle ages. The dissections were performed for educational purposes for future generations of medical students. Its construction commenced in 1637, showcasing an ornate design leaning towards wooden carved architectures. The room is richly ornamented with statues of famous physicians and anatomists. Central to this theatre is the dissection table, situated under a canopy that symbolised the universe. Unfortunately, the original theatre was destroyed in 1944 during World War II. What we see today is a faithful reconstruction from 1958. An eerie trace of ancient science, this theatre remains a symbol of the progress in understanding human body over the centuries.
sumy: Its construction commenced in 1637, showcasing an ornate design leaning towards wooden carved architectures.

base_text:
The Yarra Valley is a renowned wine-producing region in the southeast of Australia, about an hour's drive from Melbourne, the capital city of Victoria. Known predominantly for its cool-climate wines, this lush area's climate and geography make it particularly suited for growing Chardonnay, Pinot Noir, and Sparkling wines. There are more than 80 wineries in the Yarra Valley, many of which offer cellar door wine tasting experiences. In addition to its wines, the Yarra Valley boasts a thriving food scene that focuses on local and seasonal produce.

The Yarra Valley is not just about wine and food, it's also a haven for wildlife, offering visitors the chance to see native Australian animals like kangaroos and koalas in their natural habitats. It is rich in natural beauty with its rolling hills, clear running streams, and native bushland. This region also has many walking trails and picnic spots for outdoor enthusiasts. 

Dotted with charming towns and villages, the Yarra Valley is a bustling place teeming with artisan crafts, local markets, and boutique shopping. The local community hosts several events throughout the year, such as food and wine festivals. It provides a magnificent getaway for locals and tourists alike, providing a perfect blend of natural beauty, fine dining, and cultural experiences.
sumy: There are more than 80 wineries in the Yarra Valley, many of which offer cellar door wine tasting experiences.

base_text: Biperiden is a type of medication, belonging to the class of anti-Parkinson drugs called anticholinergics. This medication is designed to balance the natural substances in the brain. It's mainly used for treating symptoms of Parkinson's disease like difficulty in moving, shaking or spasms, which are known as motor symptoms. It works by blocking the action of a neurotransmitter called acetylcholine in certain areas of the brain. This action assists in reducing symptoms associated with this disease. In some cases, biperiden is used to counteract drug-induced side-effects like extrapyramidal symptoms, often seen with antipsychotic medication usage. Despite its benefits, like any other medication, it also comes with potential side effects including dry mouth, blurred vision, drowsiness and others. It is important to take this medication exactly as prescribed by the health care professional. It's crucial to inform the doctor about any other medications being taken, to avoid potential interactions. Most importantly, abrupt cessation of the medicine could lead to severe effects, hence it is recommended to follow the doctor's advice about the dosage and duration of treatment.
sumy: In some cases, biperiden is used to counteract drug-induced side-effects like extrapyramidal symptoms, often seen with antipsychotic medication usage.

base_text: Coast Guard Squadron One, commonly known as "RONONE", was a combat unit formed by the United States Coast Guard in 1965 for service during the Vietnam War. Its mission was to interdict vessels and provide coastal surveillance in South Vietnam's rivers, estuaries, and coastal waters. It consisted of 26 "Point" class cutters which were 82-foot patrol boats. These patrol boats carried out the mission to stop the flow of weapons, ammunition and supplies from North Vietnam to the southern part. Given the specialized need for combat operations, the crew members received intensive combat training prior to deployment in Vietnam. Coastal surveillance and interdiction was often done under harsh conditions. The Squadron was decommissioned in 1970 after the conclusion of its Vietnam service. This unit was the first direct U.S. Coast Guard participation in the Vietnam war. Throughout its operational tenure, Squadron One was highly effective in its mission. It left a lasting mark on the Coast Guard’s approach to maritime interdiction, homeland security, and defense operations.
sumy: Coast Guard Squadron One, commonly known as "RONONE", was a combat unit formed by the United States Coast Guard in 1965 for service during the Vietnam War.

base_text: Khalid Sheikh Mohammed is a Pakistani Islamist militant held by the United States at the Guantanamo Bay detention camp under terrorism-related charges. He is known for being the "architect" of the 9/11 attacks, the most devastating terrorist attacks in U.S. history. Before his arrest in 2003, he was a top-ranking member of the Al-Qaeda organization, working closely with Osama bin Laden. His lengthy career in terrorism also includes a variety of significant plots and attacks, such as the 1993 World Trade Center bombing. Mohammed was educated in the United States, acquiring a degree in mechanical engineering. Since his capture, he has been subjected to numerous years of detention and interrogation. He has confessed to his involvement in many crimes, though some confessions are believed to have been obtained under torture. Despite numerous legal controversies surrounding his detention, he remains one of the most significant detainees in the war on terror. Khalid Sheikh Mohammed is currently awaiting trial before a military commission. His case continues to stir debates about the application of justice in years following the 9/11 attacks.
sumy: Before his arrest in 2003, he was a top-ranking member of the Al-Qaeda organization, working closely with Osama bin Laden.

base_text: Don Mueang Tollway is a major highway located in Thailand. Its primary function is to provide a convenient, fast route for travelers between central Bangkok and Don Mueang International Airport. It is a 21.9 kilometers long expressway that has significantly reduced travel time for the commuters, especially the ones who travel frequently between the city and the airport. In 1985, it came into operation as an elevated highway. The tollway offers two separate paths, one for light vehicles with four wheels or less, and another for heavy vehicles such as trucks and buses. Toll rates are charged based on the type and size of the vehicle. For easy payments, the Tollway operator has introduced Easy Pass, a prepaid electronic system. Since the traffic volume of Bangkok is often high, the Tollway is a busy highway. Commuting on the Tollway enable travelers to bypass the city's traffic congestion. The tollway has brought about a significant improvement in the city's transportation infrastructure.
sumy: Don Mueang Tollway is a major highway located in Thailand.

base_text: Thomas Standish is a historical figure renowned in the United Kingdom, specifically in the duchy of Lancashire. He was born into the Standish family, a prominent family known for its influential role in the local politics and landed gentry in the region throughout many generations. The family held the Manor of Standish, which gave them significant local power and influence. Thomas Standish himself was an English politician who served as a Member of Parliament for Preston in Lancashire during Elizabeth I's reign in the later part of the 16th century. His political service was of high significance at a time when the role of Parliament was growing in importance. Furthermore, Standish played vital roles in various politico-religious conflicts of that era. Despite the numerous Thomas Standishes in history, he is most associated with this identity. Little is known about his personal life, although every political move he made had a profound influence at that time. His legacy forms part of the complex fabric of English history. The Standish family's influence persisted even after his death, further cementing the importance of the Standish name in England.
sumy: Thomas Standish himself was an English politician who served as a Member of Parliament for Preston in Lancashire during Elizabeth I's reign in the later part of the 16th century.

base_text: Wikisource is a digital library run by the Wikimedia Foundation. It is dedicated to the collection, preservation, and distribution of free content, primarily sourced from public domain texts. Launched in 2003, it works similarly to Wikipedia, allowing users to contribute by creating and editing pages. However, its distinct feature is that it only accepts previously published texts or documents. The contents range from poetry, novels, historical documents, speeches, to legal decisions. The project aims to transcribe, proofread, and eventually compile a searchable collection of these texts. Language wise, Wikisource is multilingual, hence, users can find texts in numerous languages. It validates the authenticity of its content by providing original scans of the documents. Due to its participatory model, it allows anyone, anytime, anywhere to access and enrich its library. Today, Wikisource remains a valuable resource, hosting hundreds of thousands of texts for public use.
sumy: It is dedicated to the collection, preservation, and distribution of free content, primarily sourced from public domain texts.

base_text: Bajaj Auto is one of the most significant two-wheeler and three-wheeler manufacturing companies in the world, based in India. The company was originally established in Mumbai in 1945, and today has its headquarters in Pune, Maharashtra. The firm was founded by Jamnalal Bajaj and is currently led by his grandson, Rajiv Bajaj. Bajaj Auto is known for its popular models including Bajaj Pulsar, Bajaj Avenger, and Bajaj Platina, among others. The company also manufactures auto rickshaws. It has a strong presence not only in the Indian market but also exports its vehicles to numerous countries globally. base_text: Craig Eiland is a prominent figure in Texas politics and law, best known for his work in the Texas House of Representatives. Eiland was particularly known for his advocacy on issues related to insurance, civil justice, and coastal matters, which were of great importance to his constituents in Galveston and Chambers Counties, which he represented. After retiring from the Texas House, Eiland transitioned to a career in law, leveraging his extensive legislative experience and knowledge of state government. Today, Eiland runs a successful law practice and continues to contribute to the legal and political landscape of Texas. Whilst in law, he has represented individuals, governmental entities and businesses in complex matters.  His work is widely respected, and he continues to have a strong influence in the state throughout his law career. Eiland is truly a distinguished figure in Texas State.

base_text: Cher Winters is a fictional character from the popular long-running British television soap opera, "Hollyoaks", broadcasted on Channel 4. She debuted on the show in 2020 and is portrayed by actress Bethannie Hare. The character is introduced as the teenage daughter of another character, Sylver McQueen, who was long lost till she found him. Cher works as a DJ and also as a hospital cleaner in the series. base_text: A Hoplite is a term originating from ancient Greece, referring to a heavily armed foot soldier. The name "Hoplite" is derived from "Hoplon," the type of shield they carried. They were the main form of infantry in the armies of city-states from the 7th to 4th centuries BC. Hoplites were known for their phalanx formation, a rectangular mass military formation usually composed entirely of heavy infantry armed with spears, pikes and large shields. Each Hoplite provided his own weapons, including a long spear, a short sword, and typically wore a bronze breastplate, helmet, and greaves for protection. They largely came from the middle classes of ancient Greek society, as they had to afford their own equipment. Their military service was both a duty and a demonstration of their social status. The armor and strategy utilized by the Hoplites played a significant role in shaping the warfare of ancient Greece. The decline of hoplite warfare began in the 4th century BC as new military tactics evolved. However, Hoplites left a lasting mark on military strategy and remain a symbol of ancient Greek culture and history.
sumy: Hoplites were known for their phalanx formation, a rectangular mass military formation usually composed entirely of heavy infantry armed with spears, pikes and large shields.

base_text: Irwin Steingut was a significant figure in American politics, best known for his role as a long-term Democratic member of the New York State Assembly. Born in 1893 in Brooklyn, New York, he was noted for his successful political career, which spanned several decades in the 20th century. His political career began in 1921 when he was first elected to the State Assembly, where he served for a period of approximately four decades. During his time in this role, he became Speaker of the New York State Assembly, a position he held for nine terms. Steingut’s impact on politics extended beyond his own career, as his son, Stanley Steingut, also served as Speaker of the New York State Assembly. Irwin Steingut died in 1952, but his legacy in New York politics remains a significant part of the state's history. His contributions to state politics and consistent commitment to the Democratic Party position him as a notable figure in New York's political history.
sumy: Irwin Steingut was a significant figure in American politics, best known for his role as a long-term Democratic member of the New York State Assembly.

base_text:
A cellular network is a communication network that uses a combination of radio signal and cellular infrastructure to provide mobile services such as voice calls, text messages, and internet access to users. The network is divided into cells, each served by a particular base station. These cells can vary in size depending upon the density of usage. 

A base station can only serve a limited area, and by dividing the coverage area into cells, the same set of frequencies can be reused in different cells. This significantly increases the capacity of the network. Each cell has a base station that communicates with mobile devices within its range. When a mobile device moves from one cell to another, the communication is seamlessly handed over to the new cell's base station.

Cellular networks operate in different frequency bands, which are allocated by the regulatory authority in each country. This technology has evolved over the years from the 1st generation (1G) to the current 5th generation (5G), providing higher capacity, speed, and features with each new generation. Cellular networks have revolutionized the way we communicate, enabling us to remain connected virtually anywhere.
sumy: The network is divided into cells, each served by a particular base station.

base_text: Charles Eady was a prominent sports figure in Tasmania, Australia during the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. He was born in 1870, and excelled as both a cricket player and an Australian rules footballer. Eady is most known for his accomplishments in cricket, having represented Tasmania in interstate competition and also having played two Tests for the Australian national team. He was a right-handed batsman and right-arm medium pace bowler. As a footballer, Eady had a successful career with the City Football Club in Hobart. He ended up captaining the club to the premiership in 1896 and 1897. Eady also served as an administrator in both cricket and football circles, and his contributions helped pave way for the growth of both sports in Tasmania. He passed away in 1945, leaving behind a sports legacy that still resonates in Australia today. He has been acknowledged by the Tasmanian Cricket Association and the Australian Cricket Board for his immense contributions to the sport of cricket in particular.
sumy: Charles Eady was a prominent sports figure in Tasmania, Australia during the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.

base_text: Knute Rockne is a well-known figure in American football history, particularly recognized for his influence in the development of the game. Born in Norway, Rockne immigrated to the U.S. and eventually played and coached football at the University of Notre Dame in Indiana. Rockne is renowned for his impressive coaching record, which includes 105 victories, 12 losses, and 5 ties. He also guided his team to several successful seasons and national championships. Apart from his record, he is often credited for popularizing the use of the forward pass, a strategy now integral to the sport. Rockne was an innovative coach whose tactics changed the course of football. When he tragically died in a plane crash in 1931, he was mourned nationally. Rockne's impact on American football is still felt today and he remains a symbol of excellence in coaching. Also, his name has been used for various causes, like Rockne's, a quick-service restaurant concept, or Studebaker Rockne, a car model.
sumy: Rockne is renowned for his impressive coaching record, which includes 105 victories, 12 losses, and 5 ties.

base_text: Robert Reinert was a significant figure in the world of film in the late 19th and early 20th century, having been known predominantly as a German screenwriter, film director, and producer. He was born in Austria in 1865 and eventually moved to Germany where he established himself in the film industry. His career spans across silent film era. Reinert entered into the cinematic world in the year 1912 and was active till 1928. Some of his most notable works include "Opium" and "Nerves". He is recognized for his ability to direct films that reflect deep psychological undertones, making his contributions innovative for the time. In addition, Reinert was the founder of the Münchener Lichtspielkunst AG (Emelka), which was a major production company in Germany. Although he didn't receive much recognition during his lifetime, he is now acknowledged as a pioneer in the arena of Expressionist cinema. Robert Reinert died in 1928. Today, he continues to be commemorated for his profound influence on German expressionist film.
sumy: Robert Reinert was a significant figure in the world of film in the late 19th and early 20th century, having been known predominantly as a German screenwriter, film director, and producer.

base_text: Carmen Monarcha is a Brazilian soprano who is best known for her work with the Dutch violinist and conductor Andre Rieu. Born in Belem, Brazil, she initially gained musical training and recognition in her home country. She later moved to The Netherlands to further her music studies at the Maastricht Academy of Music. This is around the time she met Andre Rieu, and joined his Johann Strauss Orchestra. She has performed with the Orchestra around the world, impressing audiences with her strong and emotional soprano voice. Her command over different languages has allowed her to sing in Portuguese, German, and Italian among other languages. Monarcha is particularly revered for her interpretations of classical pieces and operas. She has also participated in several of Rieu's recordings. She remains a prominent figure in the world of classical music and continues to perform at various international concerts. Despite her global success, she emphatically carries her Brazilian roots and often incorporates elements of her homeland's music in her performances.
sumy: This is around the time she met Andre Rieu, and joined his Johann Strauss Orchestra.

base_text: Puri is an integral part of Indian cuisine, known and loved for its crispy, fried texture and light, fluffy interior. It is a type of unleavened bread, which means it is made without yeast. The dough for puri consists mainly of wheat flour, water, and sometimes salt or ghee for flavor. The dough is then divided into small round pieces and rolled out into circular shapes. Each piece is deep-fried in hot oil or ghee until it puffs up, creating its signature texture. Puri is typically served as a side dish with a variety of Indian main courses. It's often enjoyed with bhaji, chole, or curry. In some regions, puri is also served during special occasions or religious ceremonies. It is also commonly consumed as part of breakfast or a snack meal. Despite its simplicity, puri is a classic example of the rich, flavorful, and diverse culinary heritage of India.
sumy: Each piece is deep-fried in hot oil or ghee until it puffs up, creating its signature texture.

base_text: Corruption in Guinea-Bissau refers to the rampant misuse of power by its public officials for personal gain, leading to systemic flaws within its governance and administrative structures. It is considered a significant problem, with the country ranking high on Transparency International's Corruption Perceptions Index. This issue plays into various sectors, including politics, policing, and business, causing a lack of faith in public institutions among the citizens. This corruption has undermined the country's development and increased poverty levels, as funds meant for public services have been embezzled. Further, Guinea-Bissau's location on the West African coast has turned it into a transit hub for international drug trafficking, leading to an increase in corruption within law enforcement and judicial systems. The corruption issue also impedes foreign investments and leads to human rights abuses. Despite efforts at the national and international levels to combat corruption, progress is hindered by a cycle of political instability and lack of political will. Public officials and politicians engage in corrupt practices without any significant fear of punishment making it a deep-rooted problem. Tackling corruption is seen as a key step to unlock Guinea-Bissau's potential and improve living conditions for its citizens. Therefore, corruption in Guinea-Bissau represents a deep-rooted systemic problem which inhibits national progress.
sumy: This issue plays into various sectors, including politics, policing, and business, causing a lack of faith in public institutions among the citizens.

base_text: The term '1938 United States House of Representatives elections' refers to the elections that took place in 1938 to elect the members of the United States House of Representatives, which is the lower house of the United States Congress. These elections occurred in the middle of President Franklin D. Roosevelt's second term, during the Great Depression. In these elections, the Republican Party made significant gains, while the Democratic Party, despite suffering losses, managed to retain a majority in the House. The elections were seen as a referendum on the New Deal programs introduced by Roosevelt. The results were seen as a backlash against Roosevelt's attempt to 'pack' the Supreme Court and the ongoing economic challenges. All 435 seats in the House of Representatives were up for election. The Republicans gained 81 seats from the Democrats. After the elections, the Democrats held 262 seats, and the Republicans held 169. It was a critical moment in legislative history as it marked a halt in the expansion of the New Deal.
sumy: These elections occurred in the middle of President Franklin D. Roosevelt's second term, during the Great Depression.

base_text: The Thomas Jefferson Star for Foreign Service is a prestigious award given by the United States Department of State. It's awarded to individuals in the Foreign Service who have made significant contributions or demonstrated remarkable courage and leadership in situations of international significance. This award was established by the U.S. Congress in 1994, named after the third U.S President, Thomas Jefferson, recognizing his legacy as the first Secretary of State. Those who are eligible for the award are not just those who were in the line of duty but also U.S. citizens who were killed or suffered serious injuries while working on behalf of the U.S. government overseas. The award is made in the form of a gold medal, which is often accompanied by a rosette in the colors of the department’s flag. It's presented by the Secretary of State. The Jefferson Star is a high honor within the Department of State and it reflects the United States' appreciation for the recipients' services. It's one of the highest awards in the Foreign Service. Moreover, it represents exceptional dedication to duty by those serving the United States abroad.
sumy: It's awarded to individuals in the Foreign Service who have made significant contributions or demonstrated remarkable courage and leadership in situations of international significance.

base_text: FC Groningen is a professional Dutch football club based in Groningen, the capital city of the eponymous province in the Netherlands. The club was founded in 1915 and it currently competes in the Eredivisie, the top tier of professional football in the Netherlands. It plays its home matches in the Hitachi Capital Mobility Stadium, which has a seating capacity of around 22,500 spectators. The club's traditional colours are green and white, reflected in their home kits. FC Groningen gained significant recognition when they won the KNVB Cup in 2015, their first major trophy in their club history. The club has also produced several notable players, particularly Arjen Robben, who has had an illustrious career at clubs like Chelsea, Real Madrid, and Bayern Munich. FC Groningen focuses heavily on youth development, with many players coming through their youth academy. FC Groningen is known for its passionate supporters, who are some of the most dedicated in Dutch football. The club stands as a symbol of pride for the city and province of Groningen. FC Groningen in its entirety embodies the spirit, determination, and resilience of Dutch football.
sumy: It plays its home matches in the Hitachi Capital Mobility Stadium, which has a seating capacity of around 22,500 spectators.

base_text: Phoradendron juniperinum is a type of mistletoe, more commonly known as juniper mistletoe. Unlike most plants, it's a hemiparasitic species, meaning it relies on a host plant for some of its nutritional needs. It's native to North America, particularly the region encompassing northern Mexico and the southwestern United States. Upon finding a suitable host, which is often a juniper tree, Phoradendron juniperinum establishes itself by penetrating the host's bark and drawing out necessary nutrients. Despite this parasitic behavior, it is still capable of photosynthesis, hence the term 'hemiparasitic'. These plants produce small, sticky berries that are spread by birds who eat them and later excrete the seeds onto other trees. Phoradendron juniperinum usually do not kill their hosts but can weaken them and make them more susceptible to other forms of stress or disease. Despite the harm to their hosts, these mistletoes are significant contributors to biodiversity, providing valuable resources for a variety of animals. However, in forestry settings they can be considered a pest. Due to their distinct lifestyle, control methods involve physically removing the plant or using specific pesticides.
sumy: Despite this parasitic behavior, it is still capable of photosynthesis, hence the term 'hemiparasitic'.

base_text: Eilean Glas Lighthouse is a significant landmark that's located on the Isle of Scalpay, in the Outer Hebrides of Scotland. The term 'Eilean Glas' translates as 'green island' in Scottish Gaelic. The lighthouse was one of the original four lighthouses to be commissioned by the Northern Lighthouse Board in 1786. Specifically, it was established by Thomas Smith, who was the stepfather of the famous lighthouse engineer, Robert Stevenson. Initially, the lighthouse was just a simple tower with a coal fire on top. However, it was reconstructed in 1824 using Stevenson’s design and remains this way to this day. It stands at 37 metres tall and its light can be seen up to 44 kilometres away. The lighthouse was automated in 1978 and is still in use today. Despite being in a remote location, it’s a popular destination for hikers and wildlife watchers. Eilean Glas Lighthouse is recognised for its historical significance, its picturesque setting and its contributions to maritime safety.
sumy: Eilean Glas Lighthouse is a significant landmark that's located on the Isle of Scalpay, in the Outer Hebrides of Scotland.

base_text: Rhett Allain is a prominent figure in the field of physics and science education. He is an Associate Professor of Physics at Southeastern Louisiana University. Known for simplifying complex scientific concepts, Allain specializes in creating engaging ways to teach physics. Apart from being an educator, he also contributes to the field as an author. His work involves blogs and textbooks about physics, with one popular book being "Just Enough Physics." Additionally, Allain is very active in media and writes about physics for the online magazine "Wired." In his articles, he explains scientific principles using everyday objects to make things more understandable. He also maintains a personal blog called "Dot Physics," where he answers complex physics questions. Throughout his career, Allain has bridged the gap between academic physics and common understanding, making the subject more accessible. He delivers public talks and hosts workshops on physics education, further demonstrating his commitment to the field.

base_text: David Beaton of Melgund was a significant figure in Scottish history during the 16th century. He was born into the influential Beaton family who were closely connected with the Scottish court. David came into prominence during the reign of James V, where he converted his familial connections into political influence. He was made a cardinal in 1538 and further elevated to the position of Archbishop of St. Andrews in 1539. His influential role in Scottish politics was further solidified when he essentially became the ruler of Scotland as regent for the infant Mary, Queen of Scots. Beaton was a staunch proponent of the Catholic Church at a time when Protestant ideas were beginning to take hold in Scotland. He was infamous for his persecution of Protestant reformers, which culminated with the burning of George Wishart, a Protestant preacher, in 1546. His actions incited religious tensions, eventually resulting in his murder, also in 1546. Despite his controversial status, he was an influential force in maintaining Scotland's alliance with France and resisting reforming influences from England. His legacy is, thus, intricately tied with the religious and political landscape of 16th century Scotland.
sumy: David Beaton of Melgund was a significant figure in Scottish history during the 16th century.

base_text: The term 'Iris subg. Iris' represents a subgenus within the larger Iris species group. To be precise, 'Iris subg. Iris' is a taxonomic division that exists directly under the genus rank in the plant classification hierarchy. This naming is part of a botanical taxonomic process called plant nomenclature, where each classification level is given binomial Latin names. In this context, the first Iris refers to the genus, while the second refers to the subgenus itself. This subgenus consists mainly of hardy rhizomatous species, including well-known varieties such as Iris germanica and Iris pallida. These plants are often recognized by their classic fan arrangement of leaves and beautiful spring-summer flowers. They're predominantly found in the temperate regions of Europe and Asia. Having varying levels of taxonomy helps botanists and gardeners alike in understanding and categorizing the complexity and diversity among species within the Iris genus.
sumy: This naming is part of a botanical taxonomic process called plant nomenclature, where each classification level is given binomial Latin names.

base_text: Davao City is a city located on the island of Mindanao in the Philippines. It is known for being one of the largest cities in the world in terms of land area, covering more than 2,400 square kilometers. Davao City is the third most populous city in the Philippines, and it is the center of Metro Davao, which is the third most populous metropolitan area in the Philippines. It serves as the main trade, commerce, and industry hub of Mindanao and the regional center of Davao Region. Davao City has a mayor-council type of government, and it’s considered as one of the safest in the country. Its famous landmarks include Mount Apo, which is the highest mountain in the Philippines, and the majestic Philippine Eagle, which is the country's national bird and considered the largest species of eagles in the world. It is also known for its durian fruit and for hosting the annual Kadayawan Festival. Besides its bounty of natural and cultural attractions, Davao City is a thriving modern metropolis, with shopping malls, restaurants, and nightlife options. Its diverse mix of indigenous tribes, migrant settlers, and expatriates contribute to the city's unique socially cultural landscape. Davao City offers an interesting mix of rural and urban attractions, a gateway to the natural wonders of southern Mindanao.
sumy: It is known for being one of the largest cities in the world in terms of land area, covering more than 2,400 square kilometers.

base_text: The Carbon Lehigh Intermediate Unit (CLIU) is an educational institution serving two Pennsylvania counties: Carbon and Lehigh. It's one of the 29 intermediate units in Pennsylvania, created in 1971 to provide services to local school districts. They offer a variety of programs ranging from special education, instructional services, technical services, and more. The CLIU also offers professional development for educators. The goal of these units is to facilitate cooperation among schools and give them access to specialized staff and resources. Moreover, the CLIU acts as a liaison between the school districts and the Pennsylvania Department of Education. The intermediate unit is governed by a board of directors that comprises of representatives from each of its constituent school districts. The financial support for CLIU primarily comes from contracts with its member school districts, state and federal programs. It aims to help improve education and give students a better chance at success. In essence, CLIU provides supplementary educational, administrative, and management services to its associated school districts.
sumy: The financial support for CLIU primarily comes from contracts with its member school districts, state and federal programs.

base_text: The Access to COVID-19 Tools (ACT) Accelerator is a global collaboration focused on accelerating the development and production of COVID-19 tests, treatments, and vaccines. It was launched in April 2020 by the World Health Organization and partners. Its goal is to ensure that all countries, regardless of their wealth, have equal access to new COVID-19 tools. The ACT Accelerator aims to bring together governments, health organizations, scientists, businesses, and philanthropists. It is organized into four pillars of work: diagnostics, therapeutics, vaccines, and health system connector. Each pillar is responsible for a specific part of the response to the pandemic. The hope is that by pooling resources and expertise, the ACT Accelerator can help to end the COVID-19 pandemic as quickly as possible. It serves as a system designed to promote collective commitment and action in combating this global health crisis. Additionally, the ACT Accelerator also aims to rebuild health systems to be more resilient in the face of future pandemics. This alliance shows the importance and power of global solidarity in addressing health crises.
sumy: The ACT Accelerator aims to bring together governments, health organizations, scientists, businesses, and philanthropists.

base_text: An Automatic Identification System (AIS) is a tracking technology used predominantly in maritime environments. It uses transceivers on ships and tracking stations on both ships and on the shore to provide real-time information about a ship's identity, position, course, and speed. The system was originally developed to improve maritime safety, primarily through collision avoidance. Today, it is mandatory for international voyaging ships and for passenger carriers to have an AIS installed. The system works by exchanging data with other nearby ships and AIS Base stations, using a regular VHS radio basis. This data can help ships navigate through crowded harbours and at night. It also assists port authorities in traffic control and enables rescue operations to locate vessels more easily. AIS is especially valuable in avoiding collision in busy sea lanes filled with large ships. Despite its many benefits, it does not replace the need for careful navigation and standard precautions. Essentially, AIS is an essential tool for enhancing maritime safety and efficiency.
sumy: The system works by exchanging data with other nearby ships and AIS Base stations, using a regular VHS radio basis.

base_text: No. 1 Squadron RAAF refers to the first squadron of the Royal Australian Air Force (RAAF). It is one of the most historic squadrons in the Australian military, having been initially formed as part of the Australian Flying Corps in January 1916, before being re-formed as part of the RAAF in 1922. It played influential roles in both World War I and II. The squadron has participated in several significant military operations, including the conflicts in the Middle East. The squadron's primary role has shifted over time, but it typically handles air interdiction and close air support duties. It has also been involved in patrol and surveillance operations. Based at RAAF Base Amberley in Queensland, the squadron currently operates F/A-18F Super Hornets. The motto of No. 1 Squadron is Videmus Agamus which means 'We see and we act'. It continues to be an active squadron in the Australian military.
sumy: It played influential roles in both World War I and II.

base_text: Pravda is a Russian term that translates to "truth" in English. However, it is most recognized for its association with a prominent newspaper that functioned as the official mouthpiece of the Communist Party in the Soviet Union. The Pravda newspaper was established in 1912 and played a crucial role in the Bolshevik Party's propaganda machinery, disseminating party ideologies and news to the masses. Under the leadership of Lenin and then later Stalin, Pravda was used as a tool to control information and mold public opinion. Until the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991, Pravda remained a significant part of the country's political machinery. But despite the collapse of the Soviet Union, Pravda continues to exist even today, albeit with a lesser role and influence. Its format changed over the years from a broadsheet to an online publication. It is still seen as a mouthpiece for specific political views and its portrayal of news is controversial due to accusations of fake news and disinformation. Therefore, while Pravda may mean truth, its legacy in relation to truth in journalism is complex and often challenged.
sumy: Pravda is a Russian term that translates to "truth" in English.

base_text: CKON-FM is a radio station that is licensed to the St. Regis Mohawk Reservation in Akwesasne, a territory spanning parts of the United States and Canada. The station started its operations in 1984, and it is completely owned and operated by the local Mohawk community. CKON-FM broadcasts at 97.3 FM, serving the Akwesasne community and the surrounding areas. Primarily, it features various formats including adult contemporary, country, and classic rock music, along with the broadcast of local news, weather forecasts, and sports. Additionally, it provides programming relevant and important to the Akwesasne Mohawk community like native languages lessons. CKON-FM's content largely reflects the interests and concerns of the Mohawk community. It is a vital source of information and entertainment for the Akwesasne people. This radio station, being a community-oriented one, plays a significant role in local sociocultural life. CKON-FM stands as an epitome of locally owned and operated indigenous radio. Its success has served as a model for other indigenous communities to create and run their own radio stations.
sumy: Additionally, it provides programming relevant and important to the Akwesasne Mohawk community like native languages lessons.

base_text: Albert Wheeler Todd was a renowned American architect who was born in the late 19th century and actively practiced in the early to mid 20th century. Born in 1883, he completed his education in architecture at Cornell University. His architectural contributions were mainly in New York city. One of his most well-known work is the New York Athletic Club located in Central Park South, for which he won the 1929 Architectural League of New York Gold Medal in architecture. He not only contributed to the aesthetic realm of the city, but also to its functionality; he was responsible for rebuilding the city's sewer system. Albert Todd also helped design several religious edifices, most notably churches. His work extended beyond New York; he was one of the architects involved in designing the Cleveland Union Terminal in Ohio, in collaboration with Graham, Anderson, Probst & White. He was a fellow of the American Institute of Architects. He died in 1948 leaving behind a legacy of significant architectural designs. Even today, his designs are essential elements of the cityscapes he touched.
sumy: One of his most well-known work is the New York Athletic Club located in Central Park South, for which he won the 1929 Architectural League of New York Gold Medal in architecture.

base_text: Silvertown railway station is a former station located in the Silvertown area within the city of London, England. This station was first opened in 1863 by the Eastern Counties and Thames Junction Railway. It was based in the London borough of Newham on the North Woolwich line. Silvertown railway station was named after the local area, famous for its silver refinery, hence getting the moniker, Silvertown. The station was key for workers traveling to the numerous factories set up during the Industrial revolution. The station was generally used for passenger services and had regular public transport links. However, due to air raid damage in World War II, it suffered severe damage and was subsequently closed for repair in 1944. Unfortunately, it never reopened for passenger services post the repairs. The station's platforms were demolished in the late 20th century. Currently, the location is absorbed into the Docklands Light Railway as part of their line extension.
sumy: This station was first opened in 1863 by the Eastern Counties and Thames Junction Railway.

base_text: Alfred Jansa was an Austrian military officer and author, born in 1897. He is most recognized for his work during World War II, especially for drafting a plan known as the "Jansa Plan." This plan proposed reorganizing the military formations of the Austrian army. Despite the annexation of Austria into Germany in 1938, Jansa remained loyal to Austria, and was dismissed from his position as a result. After the war, he worked as a military writer and historian, contributing to the knowledge and understanding of Austria's military history. He also served as a military advisor to the Austrian government after the war. Known for his patriotism and military strategy, Jansa's work continues to be studied and respected in military and historical fields. Alfred Jansa died in 1964.
sumy: Alfred Jansa was an Austrian military officer and author, born in 1897.

base_text: The BYD F3DM is an advanced, hybrid compact sedan manufactured by BYD Auto, a part of the Chinese multinational company, BYD Co Ltd. The name itself means "Dual Mode", indicating its ability to operate in both electric and hybrid modes. It is considered one of the world's first mass-produced plug-in hybrid vehicles. It has two electric motors and a small internal combustion engine. The first electric motor can work independently or in conjunction with the engine, depending upon the driving condition. The second electric motor is designed to work only with the combustion engine to increase power. The BYD F3DM can cover a distance of around 37 miles purely on electric charge, after which the gasoline engine kicks in. Introduced in China in 2008, the vehicle's goal was to provide a low-emission driving option. However, it was not globally marketed due to its high cost and BYD's limited international presence. Over time, the F3DM has been phased out and replaced by more advanced models in BYD's lineup.
sumy: The name itself means "Dual Mode", indicating its ability to operate in both electric and hybrid modes.
