base_text: West Ealing railway station is a significant transportation hub located in West Ealing, a district in the London Borough of Ealing, England. It was originally opened in 1871 by the Great Western Railway and remains a key part of the Great Western Main Line that runs from London Paddington to Bristol. This station is significantly used by local residents due to its strategic location. The station is managed by Great Western Railway, who also provide most of the train services. It's situated in Travelcard Zone 3, making it conveniently accessible for commuters within the London area. It offers not only mainline services but also commuter services into central London. base_text: Andrew Tallon was a renowned architectural historian, medievalist, and professor known for his application of advanced technology in the field of art history. Born in Belgium in 1969, Tallon studied art history at the University of Paris-Sorbonne before moving to the U.S. He earned a Ph.D. from Columbia University and became an associate professor at Vassar College in New York. Tallon is best known for his work on Gothic architecture, particularly his digital mapping of the Notre-Dame Cathedral in Paris. Using laser scanners, he captured the cathedral's structure with extreme precision, generating a meticulous 3D model. His dedication to this unique research method created a valuable archive that gained renewed significance after the cathedral’s fire in 2019. Tallon authored several books and was regarded as a pioneer in his field. He passed away in 2018 after battling brain cancer. His work continues to influence the way we understand, preserve, and restore historical architectural structures.
sumy: He earned a Ph.D. from Columbia University and became an associate professor at Vassar College in New York.

base_text: Les Automatistes were a group of avant-garde artists from Quebec, Canada centered around the painter Paul-Émile Borduas. The group formed in the 1940s and included artists from diverse fields like painting, dance, drama, and writing. They were heavily influenced by surrealism and abstract expressionism, and their work prioritized spontaneity, individual creativity, and the unconscious. The group is named after the technique of automatism, which involves creating art without conscious control or planning. The Automatistes aimed to achieve complete artistic and intellectual freedom, rebelling against the conservative societal norms of their time. They are famous for the "Refus Global", a manifesto decrying the stifling atmosphere of Catholicism and the lack of creative freedom. The impact of Les Automatistes extended beyond the art world, contributing to the Quiet Revolution in Quebec. Their work has left a lasting legacy on Canadian and global art. The Automatistes movement ended in the early 1960s, but its influence is still seen today in contemporary art.
sumy: Les Automatistes were a group of avant-garde artists from Quebec, Canada centered around the painter Paul-Émile Borduas.

base_text: St Mary, Our Lady of Victories Church in Dundee, is a prominent religious site in Scotland, United Kingdom. The St Mary, Our Lady of Victories Church is a symbol of Dundee's rich cultural and religious heritage.
sumy: The church is dedicated to St Mary, often interpreted as Our Lady of Victories, a title attributed to the Blessed Virgin Mary.

base_text: Brule County is a county located in the U.S. state of South Dakota. As of the 2010 Census, its population was 5,255. base_text: The Emin Pasha Relief Expedition was a rescue mission in the late 19th century, initiated to save Emin Pasha, the Governor of Equatoria in the southernmost province of the Egyptian Sudan. Officially known as Dr. Eduard Schnitzer, Emin had been appointed by the Khedive of Egypt but was cut off by a Mahdist uprising in 1885. With his province threatened by the Mahdi uprising, Emin was under the threat of getting captured, which prompted a rescue mission led by famed explorer, Henry Morton Stanley. The expedition was mainly carried out in the eastern part of the Congo Basin and was one of the most celebrated European explorations of Africa. The journey started in 1887 and took three years to complete, facing several challenges including disease, hostile tribes, and difficult geography. Despite severe hardships, the expedition reached Emin in 1888, convincing him to leave Sudan with his followers. The expedition returned to the east coast of Africa in 1890, concluding the mission. The Emin Pasha Relief Expedition is famous not only for its rescue mission but also because it resulted in significant advances in African ethnography, botany, and geography.
sumy: With his province threatened by the Mahdi uprising, Emin was under the threat of getting captured, which prompted a rescue mission led by famed explorer, Henry Morton Stanley.

base_text: William Clavering-Cowper was the 2nd Earl Cowper, an English nobleman belonging to the 18th century, known for his political role in Great Britain. He was born in 1709 and served as Lord Lieutenant of Hertfordshire, the county in England where his family owned large estates. Clavering-Cowper's father, William Cowper, was the 1st Earl Cowper and a noted Lord Chancellor of Great Britain. When he passed away in 1723, Clavering-Cowper inherited his father's titles and became the 2nd Earl Cowper. He was a part of the House of Lords as a Whig, which was a political faction that played a significant role in British politics at that time. Apart from his political duties, he also served as the Ranger of Richmond Park, a royal park in west London. He died in 1764, which led to the passing of his title to his half-brother, George Nassau Clavering-Cowper. As an influential political figure and one of the British nobility, his life and work have often been studied by historians. His main other title was Viscount Fordwich, a title he held in addition to Earl Cowper. His contributions to the political landscape of 18th-century England represented his noble lineage's significant role.
sumy: William Clavering-Cowper was the 2nd Earl Cowper, an English nobleman belonging to the 18th century, known for his political role in Great Britain.

base_text: Robin Skynner was a renowned British psychiatrist and psychotherapist, who was best known for his expertise in exploring and treating psychological issues within families. He was born on August 8, 1922, and died on February 12, 2000. His work in the field of family and marital therapy has been highly influential, internationally recognized and acknowledged. Skynner developed innovative techniques for these therapies, including that of group analysis. He worked closely with comedian and mental health activist John Cleese, co-authoring two books on relationships and families. The most famous of these is "Families and How to Survive them". His approach and methods are widely used in therapeutic treatments today. Skynner was also the founder of the Institute of Family Therapy and the Group-Analytic Practice. He was instrumental in highlighting the significance of relationships in shaping the mental health of individuals. Skynner’s work has had profound impacts in the understanding of family dynamics and its impact on mental health.
sumy: Skynner developed innovative techniques for these therapies, including that of group analysis.

base_text: The solar eclipse of October 23, 2014 was a significant astronomical event. This was a partial solar eclipse, meaning the moon did not completely cover the sun, but instead moved across the sun's disk partially obscuring it. This event was visible from North America and eastern Pacific Ocean. In the areas of greatest eclipse, the moon covered approximately 81% of the sun's diameter. The eclipse fell in the late afternoon or early evening for most viewers in North America, making it more challenging to see. The eclipse occurred when the new moon moved between the Earth and the sun. More specifically, its occurrence took place in the second half of 2014's lunar month, or lunation 1133. This was the second and final solar eclipse in 2014, the first happened on April 29. Observation of the event required the use of safe viewing techniques and equipment to protect observers' eyes. Despite the challenges in viewing, it was still an interesting event for astronomy enthusiasts.
sumy: This event was visible from North America and eastern Pacific Ocean.

base_text: The American Educational Research Association (AERA) is a professional organization for individuals who work in the field of education research. Established in 1916, its headquarters is currently in Washington D.C., USA. Over the years, it has grown in its outreach and aims at improving the educational process by encouraging scholarly research. This organization is responsible for publishing a range of academic research papers and journals. AERA promotes the use of research for improving education and serves public interests by providing scholarly insights into educational issues. AERA has a network of more than 25,000 members that include researchers, educators, and students from various educational fields. Overall, AERA is a leading voice in setting standards for education research and in the promotion of the application of scientific methodology in investigating educational phenomena.

base_text: "Cat and Mouse in Partnership" is a term that originally denotes a Germany fairy tale collected by the Brothers Grimm. The story involves a cat and a mouse that decide to live and store food together for winter. They hide a pot of fat in a church for safekeeping. But the cat, driven by greed and cunning, deceives the mouse and ends up eating the stored fat bit by bit. The mouse, none the wiser, eventually finds out about the deceit and suffers from the cat's treachery. In current usage, 'cat and mouse in partnership' can refer to a relationship where one party tricks the other, often exploiting the trust and ignorance of the other. It's a scenario where a seemingly mutual agreement or partnership is utilized by one party for their selfish gains. The term applies to situations where there's deceit, manipulation, and breach of trust, often leading to the harm of the manipulated party. It highlights the naive and unsuspecting nature of one party and the cunning, deceptive nature of the other.
sumy: "Cat and Mouse in Partnership" is a term that originally denotes a Germany fairy tale collected by the Brothers Grimm.

base_text: Torbay is a town located on the eastern side of the Avalon Peninsula in Newfoundland and Labrador, Canada. This town is part of the St. John's Metropolitan Area and is situated about 12 kilometers north of the capital city, St. John's. Terms like “Newfoundland” and “Labrador” refer to the easternmost province of Canada which is made up of the island of Newfoundland and mainland Labrador. Torbay, with its rich history and culture, is named after the Torbay town in Devon, England. The town is characterized by numerous beaches, ponds, and two rivers, Flatrock River and North Pond River. Torbay is also popular for its three iconic trails namely: Father Troy's Trail, Killick Coast Trail, and Cobbler's Path. It attracts tourists with its scenic beauty and coastal views. The town of Torbay is also recognized for hosting the annual Torbay Folk Arts Festival.
sumy: This town is part of the St. John's Metropolitan Area and is situated about 12 kilometers north of the capital city, St. John's.

base_text: Geoffroi de Charney, also known as Geoffrey de Charny, was a French knight from the 14th century known for his military exploits during the Hundred Years' War. He is renowned for his writings on chivalry and knighthood, as well as for his alleged possession of the Shroud of Turin, which is believed by some to be the burial cloth of Jesus Christ. He was a highly respected figure in his time, known for his valor and skill in battle. Geoffrey de Charny was killed during the Battle of Poitiers in 1356. He was a member of the Order of the Star, a chivalric order founded by King John II of France. His written works are highly valued as primary sources of information on the mindset and code of conduct of the medieval knight. Despite his historical significance, many aspects of his life and deeds remain shrouded in mystery. His connection to the Shroud of Turin has made him a figure of interest in the study of religious relics. He remains a celebrated figure in French history and a symbol of medieval chivalry. Geoffroi de Charney stands as an emblematic figure of the complex interplay between warfare, chivalry, and religion in the Middle Ages.
sumy: Geoffroi de Charney, also known as Geoffrey de Charny, was a French knight from the 14th century known for his military exploits during the Hundred Years' War.

base_text: The Church of St Michael is a historical religious establishment located in the village of Blackford, Somerset, in the United Kingdom. It is a structurally significant building, dating back to the 13th century, although much of what stands today was rebuilt in the 19th century. It is dedicated to St Michael, a biblical archangel, commonly considered a warrior saint. The church is designed in a predominantly Gothic architectural style. It is best known for its beautiful stained glass remnants and an ancient clock thought to be one of the oldest in England. Recognised for its historical importance, it has been listed as a Grade I building by English Heritage. Communities continue to use the church for worship and various ceremonies. Its churchyard also contains many fascinating historic gravestones. It forms a significant part of Blackford's heritage and continues to stand as a symbol of the village's long history. In addition, it offers a serene space for reflection and prayer for parishioners and tourists alike.
sumy: It is best known for its beautiful stained glass remnants and an ancient clock thought to be one of the oldest in England.

base_text: Gregory Prince is a well-known figure in the fields of microbiology, history, and religious studies. He is a successful businessman, who co-founded Virion Systems, Inc. which developed measures to prevent respiratory infections in infants. He is also recognized for his pioneering research on respiratory syncytial virus. Later, he sold the company and switched to historical research and writing. Prince is renowned in the sphere of Mormon studies for his extensive research and publications, including books like "David O. McKay and the Rise of Modern Mormonism." Despite being a stalwart member of the Mormon Church, he is known for his progressive views on controversial issues within the community. He also runs a philanthropic foundation, the Madison House Autism Foundation, which supports adults with autism. Prince has thus made significant contributions to science, history, religion, and philanthropy.
sumy: Gregory Prince is a well-known figure in the fields of microbiology, history, and religious studies.

base_text: Maniraptora is a term used in the field of paleontology, referring to a group of dinosaurs. These dinosaurs are a clade of coelurosaurian theropods that evolved during the late Jurassic period. This group includes birds and their closest dinosaurian relatives. Maniraptorans are characterized by long, grasping arms and hands, and in many cases, feathers. They are known for their agile bodies and quick movements. Some maniraptorans were herbivores, but most were carnivores. The name Maniraptora means 'hand snatchers', aptly describing their distinctive grasping hands. They are seen as an evolutionary transition, leading to the development of birds. Some well-known dinosaurs, such as the Velociraptor and the Tyrannosaurus Rex, are part of this group. Much of what we know about them comes from fossils which display their unique skeletal structure and, in some cases, impressions of their feather patterns.
sumy: These dinosaurs are a clade of coelurosaurian theropods that evolved during the late Jurassic period.

base_text: Torpids is an annual rowing event that takes place in Oxford, England, and is an important part of university tradition. It is organized by the Oxford University Rowing Clubs and involves various colleges within the university. During the event, participants row in boats known as eights, which accommodate eight rowers and a coxswain. These races are held on the Isis River, usually in late February to early March. It is structured as a "bumps race," meaning boats start at equal distances, and each boat tries to "bump" the one in front to move up the rankings. The term "Torpids" virtually means sluggish or dormant, suggesting the historical purpose of the event during the colder months to keep the rowers active. When a boat is "bumped," it drops out for the rest of the day but will row again the next day, starting ahead of the boat that bumped it. Those that avoid being bumped are awarded blades and the crew members are allowed to paint their oar handles. Torpids lasts for four days and is a highly anticipated event, often drawing large spectators. The competition is an intense and exciting challenge that showcases the sporting prowess and team spirit of the Oxford colleges.
sumy: During the event, participants row in boats known as eights, which accommodate eight rowers and a coxswain.

base_text: Expedition Robinson 2001 is the fifth season of the popular Swedish reality television show, Expedition Robinson, that premiered on 15 September 2001. The concept was essentially a survival competition, which took place in Malaysia. The series is essentially a contest of survival, where contestants are divided into two teams and perform various physical tasks. Each week there would be a voting section where each team could vote off a teammate. This particular season of the show is well known because it introduced a rule allowing contestants who had been voted off to return to the show. The competitors endured isolated living conditions, lack of food and harsh weather elements to win. The ultimate aim was to be the last person standing and thus win a cash prize. This 2001 season was won by Jan Emanuel Johansson. The show was popular and contributed significantly to the widespread popularity and adoption of reality television. The show is often credited with giving rise to other versions in different countries, including the American Survivor series.
sumy: The concept was essentially a survival competition, which took place in Malaysia.

base_text: A membrane is a thin, pliable layer that surrounds something. It is often found in both living and non-living things. In living organisms, it has the role of separating an organism's cells, or its inside from its outside environment. This separation allows the cell to function properly, protecting it from harmful substances while permitting essential materials to pass through. For instance, the cellular membrane is vital for a cell's survival, as it mediates the transportation of nutrients and waste products. In non-living things, membranes like those in mechanical devices or tech gadgets, often serve as protective barriers or filters. Membranes can also serve as semi-permeable barriers, which means only certain substances can cross them. They are vital for various biological functions and technological processes. Importantly, their functions and composition can vastly differ depending on their purpose and location. Overall, membranes are thin structures serving as protective or functional layers.
sumy: It is often found in both living and non-living things.

base_text: Gayle Barron is not a term but a notable person in the realm of long-distance running. Born in the United States, she is a former professional marathon runner who gained fame during the 1970s. Barron is best known for her victory in the 1978 Boston Marathon, where she was the first woman to break the two-and-a-half-hour barrier. This achievement made her a pioneer in women's marathon running. Beyond this, Gayle Barron has continued to contribute to the sport by working to promote physical fitness and health. She has co-authored a book on running and has served in roles as the director of the Atlanta Track Club's Peachtree Road Race. Despite the passage of time, her legacy in the sport of marathon running continues. Her achievement of breaking records and gender barriers in marathon running renders her an iconic figure in women's sports history. Therefore, in running circles, the name Gayle Barron might be invoked to signify female accomplishment and pioneering spirit.
sumy: This achievement made her a pioneer in women's marathon running.

base_text: Ohau Railway Station is a railway station located in Ohau, a small rural community in New Zealand. It was one of many similar stations built as part of the New Zealand national railway network for passenger and freight transportation. Specifically, this station was part of the North Island Main Trunk Line. The Ohau Railway Station was opened in 1886 and played a crucial role in transporting goods and people throughout the country, contributing to the growth of the local economy. However, with the decline in rail transportation, due to advances in road transportation technology, it was officially closed in 1987. The station's life spanned a century, with its infrastructure serving various purposes after closure, including being used for grain storage. While the station no longer operates, it stands as a representation of New Zealand's historical landscape. Currently, the structure of the station and tracks are not in use for any railway services. Despite closure, the station's existence provides insight into the significant role rail transport played in New Zealand’s development. Nevertheless, the physical state of the station has been deteriorating due to lack of maintenance since its closure.
sumy: Specifically, this station was part of the North Island Main Trunk Line.

base_text: Mathur is a small village located in the Krishnagiri district of the southern Indian state, Tamil Nadu. Containing fewer than 600 inhabitants, Mathur is known for its distinct cultural heritage and rural lifestyle. Its geographical position in the Krishnagiri district marks it as a place of interest for nature enthusiasts, given Krishnagiri's reputation as a land of hills and thick vegetation. Economy in Mathur is predominantly based on agriculture and farming, producing crops such as mango, rice and coconut. The main language spoken in this village is Tamil. Temples form the core of spiritual and cultural life in Mathur, with regular festivals bringing villagers together. Its administrative division is under Hosur taluk of Krishnagiri district. Mathur is also near to the border of Karnataka, making it accessible to visitors and merchants from both states. It represents the simplicity and serenity of typical rural life in India. Over the years, Mathur has maintained its traditional uniqueness while progressively embracing changes brought about by broader developments in Krishnagiri district and Tamil Nadu.
sumy: Containing fewer than 600 inhabitants, Mathur is known for its distinct cultural heritage and rural lifestyle.

base_text: Parrot Cay is a private island that is part of the Turks and Caicos Islands in the British West Indies. This luxurious resort island covers an area of about 1,000 acres. Parrot Cay is renowned for its tranquility and natural beauty, with its secluded beaches, clear turquoise waters, and vibrant vegetation. This island is owned and operated by COMO Hotels and Resorts. It offers elegant beach houses and villas for stay, making it a favorite vacation spot for celebrities and individuals seeking privacy and luxury. The resort provides a variety of services like dining, spa, yoga retreats, and wellness programs. Visitors can also engage in water sports like diving and fishing. The island is also a favored venue for destination weddings due to its enchanting scenery and high-end facilities. Despite its luxury status, Parrot Cay maintains a strong commitment to sustainability and the preservation of its natural environs. To reach Parrot Cay, one needs to fly to Providenciales, the gateway island, followed by a quick boat ride.
sumy: The resort provides a variety of services like dining, spa, yoga retreats, and wellness programs.

base_text: D-flat major is a key in music that has five flats in its key signature. Those are Bb, Eb, Ab, Db, and Gb. It is considered to be the enharmonic equivalent of C-sharp major, meaning that the notes are the exact same pitch, they just have different names depending on the key context. This key is often used in music because it's thought to have a soft and calm character. As a major key, it features a happy, bright sound. It's used frequently in classical, jazz, and contemporary genres. Operating in this key can be challenging for some instrumentalists due to the large number of flats, but it's easier for those playing on a keyboard or wind instruments as the fingerings are often simpler. Musicians need to use D-flat major to evoke specific atmospheres. Famous compositions in D-flat major include Clair de Lune by Debussy and Polonaise in D-flat major by Chopin.
sumy: This key is often used in music because it's thought to have a soft and calm character.

base_text: François Kamano is a professional footballer who was born on May 2, 1996, in Kamsar, Guinea. He plays as a winger or forward, renowned for his goal-scoring abilities, agility, and skill on the ball. He began his professional career with Satellite FC in Guinea before moving to France to play for SC Bastia in 2014. After impressing in Ligue 1 with Bastia, he transferred to Bordeaux in 2016 where he further developed his skills. Kamano also represents his national team, Guinea, and has played in various international competitions. He is known for his speed, technical skills, and versatility on the field. His performances have made him a vital player for both club and country over the years. In 2019, he moved to Lokomotiv Moscow, continued to shine on the pitch. Overall, François Kamano is a distinguished figure in the world of football. Kamano's playing style and achievements make him an influential figure in the footballing world.
sumy: François Kamano is a professional footballer who was born on May 2, 1996, in Kamsar, Guinea.

base_text: DCU Saints is a professional basketball team based in Dublin, Ireland. The team is part of Dublin City University's competitive sports program. The "DCU" in the team's name stands for Dublin City University, while "Saints" represents the team's moniker. The team has a storied history and has been an integral part of Irish basketball for many years. They compete in the SuperLeague, which is the top tier basketball league in Ireland. Over the years, DCU Saints have produced many players who have shined both domestically and internationally. It is not only a sports team, but also a community of athletes, trainers, fans, and supporters. The team focuses on fostering sportsmanship, competitiveness, and the development of players. Games are often held at the DCU Sports Complex, their official home ground. Altogether, DCU Saints is a symbol of university spirit, athletic excellence, and community participation in Ireland.
sumy: DCU Saints is a professional basketball team based in Dublin, Ireland.

base_text: Jon Ungphakorn is a renowned figure from Thailand, known for his extensive work as a social activist, NGO worker, and politician. He was born in England in 1947 to a Thai father and British mother and spent his early life there before moving to Thailand. His name became prominent due to his efforts in improving human rights, health, and education among the underserved communities of Thailand. Jon co-founded the AIDS Access Foundation, aiming to offer quality healthcare services for individuals living with HIV/AIDS. He also served a term as a senator in the Thai government. He won the prestigious Magsaysay Award in 2005 for his contribution to society. Despite facing criticism and political pressures, Jon continued to work and advocate for marginalized groups. He has also written and edited numerous articles and publications focusing on social justice and equality. Even in his later years, Jon Ungphakorn remains dedicated to his humanitarian efforts, embodying his belief in social justice and empowerment. His consistent efforts make him a significant figure in Thai social reform history.
sumy: Jon co-founded the AIDS Access Foundation, aiming to offer quality healthcare services for individuals living with HIV/AIDS.

base_text: The American International School System refers to a group of private educational institutions worldwide that base their curriculum on a model of education commonly found in the United States. Typically, these schools are established outside of the U.S. to serve expatriate families, especially children of American citizens working abroad. However, they are also frequently attended by students of diverse nationalities. The curriculum is taught in English, and it often leads to an International Baccalaureate, U.S. high school diploma, or other credentials. They also aim to foster global citizenship in their students. These schools usually offer robust extracurricular programs and may have facilities for children with special educational needs. The cost of tuition varies, but it can be quite high. Most of these schools have earned accreditation from U.S. agencies. The American International School System allows students to continue their education in a familiar language and style while overseas.
sumy: The curriculum is taught in English, and it often leads to an International Baccalaureate, U.S. high school diploma, or other credentials.

base_text: The term "List of Pixar Staff" typically refers to an organized record of individuals who have been employed by Pixar Animation Studios. Pixar is an award-winning American animation studio known for creating high-quality, innovative animated movies. This list includes a broad range of roles from animators, directors, writers to production staff who collaboratively contribute to the creation of the studio's films. The list could include notable figures such as John Lasseter or Pete Docter who have significantly influenced Pixar's history. It could also encompass new employees bringing fresh ideas. Notably, many employees have been with the company for a long time marking stability in their team. The list can change as the company grows, new projects are developed, and personnel changes occur. This list is generally used for referencing purposes and can be found in publicly available sources like company's website and certain databases.
sumy: The list could include notable figures such as John Lasseter or Pete Docter who have significantly influenced Pixar's history.

base_text: Big Baldy Mountain is the highest peak located in the Little Belt Mountains of Central Montana, USA. Known as the tallest mountain in this range, Big Baldy Mountain stands at approximately 9,181 feet or about 2,800 meters above sea level. It is characterized by its distinctive bald appearance at the top, hence the name. Formed of Precambrian rocks, Big Baldy Mountain offers panoramic views across extensive grassland plains and surrounding mountain ranges. It's a relatively undisturbed wild area that houses a diverse range of wildlife such as elk, mountain goats, and bears. Despite its remote location, it attracts hikers during the summer for its moderate climbing trails which offer stunning views from the top. The mountain, however, can prove a challenging climb in winter when it's usually covered in snow. There is also a campsite nearby, making it a popular destination for outdoor lovers for camping and exploring. Big Baldy Mountain is recognized as a natural landmark in Montana, holding a significant position in the area's geographic setup. It's a symbol of the raw, untouched beauty of Central Montana’s wilderness.
sumy: Known as the tallest mountain in this range, Big Baldy Mountain stands at approximately 9,181 feet or about 2,800 meters above sea level.

base_text: Hrvatsko slovo is a term originating from Croatia and it basically translates to Croatian Word in English. It is primarily known as the title of a weekly newspaper that is circulated widely in Croatia. The newspaper was first published in 1994 and primarily focuses on topics such as Croatian culture, literature, history, and happenings. Taking a conservative and nationalist angle, Hrvatsko slovo often features literary reviews, articles, and essays penned by Croatian writers. Its content tends to lean towards nurturing and protecting Croatian national identity and heritage. As of today, Hrvatsko slovo continues to be published and is a part of the rich and diverse media landscape in Croatia. Its readers largely comprise people interested in Croatian culture and nationalism. Despite the rise of digital media, Hrvatsko slovo maintains its traditional print publication. This is not only a source of information but also a platform for debates on important social and national issues. However, like any media outlet, it has been subject to criticism and controversy due to its political and ideological stands.
sumy: Hrvatsko slovo is a term originating from Croatia and it basically translates to Croatian Word in English.

base_text: The term '2014-2016 world oil market chronology' refers to the significant events that happened in the global oil industry between 2014 and 2016. The period marked a sharp collapse in the price of oil due to a range of factors including oversupply, reduced demand, and an unpredictable geopolitical landscape. The price decline began in the Summer of 2014 when high output from the US and Russia met with low demand due to slowing economic growth globally and particularly in Europe and Asia. During this time, the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) chose not to cut production, resulting in an oil glut and further falling prices. In 2015, the trend of oversupply continued, and prices dropped to their lowest in more than a decade. Despite the slump, major oil producers, particularly in the Middle East, did not reduce their output, citing preserving market share as the reason. This market excess was exacerbated in 2016, when sanctions against Iran were lifted, allowing the country to increase its oil production. However, in late 2016, OPEC and non-OPEC countries finally agreed to curtail production in an attempt to re-balance the market, which led to an uptick in prices. The repercussions of this period on the oil industry continue to be felt as it triggered significant changes in energy policies and the global energy landscape.
sumy: The period marked a sharp collapse in the price of oil due to a range of factors including oversupply, reduced demand, and an unpredictable geopolitical landscape.

base_text: Nanmu is a term referring to a type of hardwood found predominantly in China. It is most known for its use throughout China's history, being highly prized for its superior quality. Nanmu's color can range from yellow to reddish brown and it's also known for its beautifully patterned grain. It is a term that's synonymous with durability and superior quality, due in part to its resistance to decay and insects. The hardwood is often used in construction, particularly in areas prone to dampness, as well as in carving and the making of furniture. In the past, Nanmu was also used in the making of coffins, due to its aforementioned resistance to decay. Historically, it was often associated with nobility and the high social status due to its extensive use in palaces and temples. Despite its widespread use, the harvesting of Nanmu is now regulated to prevent overexploitation. Today, items made of Nanmu, particularly antiques, are highly sought after. The term Nanmu therefore represents both a material of significant cultural and historical importance, and an enduring symbol of natural beauty and resilience.
sumy: Nanmu's color can range from yellow to reddish brown and it's also known for its beautifully patterned grain.

base_text: The Coupe de France Lord Derby is an annual knockout competition in French rugby league. This tournament, which is named after Lord Derby, the British ambassador to France who donated the original trophy in the 1930s, is one of the most prestigious events in the French rugby league calendar. The tournament follows a single-elimination format, whereby teams play against each other in one-off matches, with the losing team being immediately eliminated from the tournament. All clubs, from the amateur regional leagues to the top professional tier, are eligible to compete, promising a mix of matches and potentially thrilling upsets. The competition is organized by the French Rugby League Federation. It culminates in a final match that determines the champion. Over the years, clubs like AS Carcassonne, Lezignan Sangliers, and Saint-Gaudens Bears have been successful. The tournament encourages competition at all levels of rugby league and offers smaller clubs a chance to compete against more established teams. The Coupe de France Lord Derby is immensely popular among fans and players alike - a quintessential part of French rugby league culture.
sumy: The Coupe de France Lord Derby is an annual knockout competition in French rugby league.

base_text: Price Rite is an American supermarket chain that resides in six northeastern states of the U.S. The chain is part of the Wakefern Food Corporation, which also owns ShopRite. Price Rite primarily targets budget-conscious shoppers, offering a range of products at discounted prices. It operates on a no-frills, warehouse style outlet to keep its operation costs low. Price Rite's affordable prices are achieved by opting for private label brands and a reduced selection of products. The supermarket emphasizes that it is committed to providing the best value to its customers without sacrificing quality. Customers bag their own groceries, contributing also to the company's cost-saving efforts. Price Rite's operations are environmentally friendly as they encourage customers to use reusable shopping bags. Overall, Price Rite is a cost-effective, eco-friendly shopping option for households on a tight budget. Its model is designed to maximize savings for customers by cutting down unnecessary expenses in the retail process.
sumy: Price Rite is an American supermarket chain that resides in six northeastern states of the U.S.

base_text: Joyce Piven is not a term, but a person. She is an influential figure in American theatre and acting education. She is one of the co-founders of the renowned Piven Theatre Workshop located in Evanston, Illinois. The workshop was founded in 1971 along with her late husband Byrne Piven. Joyce Piven is best known for her teaching method that focuses on improvisation and theatre games, a method that has greatly contributed to modern theatre today. She has trained numerous successful actors, including her children Jeremy Piven and Shira Piven. Apart from her work in acting and teaching, Joyce has directed many plays. She has also worked in collaboration with several other theatre companies. In the world of acting and theatre, Joyce Piven is a highly respected figure for her contributions to acting education. Hence, in the context of theatre and actor training, Joyce Piven refers to a person known for her innovative teaching methodologies.
sumy: The workshop was founded in 1971 along with her late husband Byrne Piven.

base_text: "Soul to Preach To" is a term that is often associated with spiritual and religious practices. In typical context, it refers to an individual or a group of individuals in need of spiritual guidance or moral teaching. The "soul", in this term, refers to an entity that is open to receiving messages, teachings or principles. The "preach" part suggests the act of delivering or teaching these moral and spiritual values. In some contexts, the term can also mean persuading or influencing someone to adopt a certain belief or philosophy. Using the term "soul to preach to" implies the willingness or openness of the person to accept these teachings or influences. It may also denote a sense of responsibility in the person preaching, to guide or share wisdom with the 'soul'. This term promotes the idea of uplifting, guiding, and nurturing an individual spiritually or morally. It is frequently used in religious or spiritual contexts and can sometimes be used metaphorically in other areas of life.
sumy: In typical context, it refers to an individual or a group of individuals in need of spiritual guidance or moral teaching.

base_text: The Azerbaijan-Georgia-Romania Interconnector (AGRI) is a proposed natural gas transportation project that would connect the three named countries. The goal is to transport natural gas from Azerbaijan to Romania, via Georgia. The concept involves shipping gas across the Black Sea, providing an alternative supply for Europe, which heavily relies on Russia for its gas needs. Under this plan, the gas from Azerbaijan would be transported to Georgia through existing pipelines. In Georgia, the gas would be liquefied at a liquefaction terminal. This Liquefied Natural Gas (LNG) would then be transported by tankers across the Black Sea to Romania. In Romania, the LNG would be turned back into gas at a regasification terminal. The project has been viewed as a way of increasing energy security for Europe. However, concerns over its economic feasibility and competition from other gas projects have stalled the AGRI's progress. Despite this, the interconnector is considered an important step in diversifying Europe's gas supply routes.
sumy: This Liquefied Natural Gas (LNG) would then be transported by tankers across the Black Sea to Romania.

base_text: The Thandikulam-Omanthai offensive was a significant military operation which occurred in Sri Lanka in 2008. It was part of the larger Sri Lankan civil war that pitted the Sri Lankan government against the Tamil Tigers, a separatist group. During this offensive, the Sri Lankan army captured Thandikulam and Omanthai, two strategic locations on the A9 highway in northern Sri Lanka. This marked the end of the Line of Control that was established in 2002 during a ceasefire agreement. The Thandikulam-Omanthai offensive marked a turning point in the Sri Lankan civil war, dealing a significant blow to the military capacity of the Tamil Tigers. This offensive was also notorious for the numerous allegations of human right violations. Ultimately, this military operation represented a significant step closer to the Sri Lankan government’s victory and the end of the civil war in 2009. The offensive affected many civilians, and caused significant damage and displacement. The exact casualty figures of the Thandikulam-Omanthai offensive remain disputed. Today, the events of the offensive remain a contentious topic in Sri Lanka.
sumy: During this offensive, the Sri Lankan army captured Thandikulam and Omanthai, two strategic locations on the A9 highway in northern Sri Lanka.

base_text: The Hāsalpur inscription of Nāgavarman is one of the historical writings that provide vital knowledge about India's past, particularly from the southern region. It is a stone record dating back to the 7th century AD, located in Hasalapur, a tiny village in Karnataka, India. The inscription is named after Nāgavarman, who was supposedly a local ruler or influential person during that period. The script used in the inscription is known as 'Kannada', which is a language predominantly spoken in the Karnataka state of India. It is one of the oldest known examples of the use of this script. The inscription reveals some information about the socio-political environment of the time. It provides historians and researchers with valuable data about the then-prevailing administrative and governance systems. Besides, it also provides insights into the cultural and religious aspects of society during Nāgavarman's era. While the inscription is not elaborative, it is one of the key pieces of evidence pointing towards the early development and usage of Kannada script. Therefore, the Hāsalpur inscription of Nāgavarman holds immense historical significance for Indian history and linguistic studies.
sumy: The inscription is named after Nāgavarman, who was supposedly a local ruler or influential person during that period.

base_text: Kasym Khan was a prominent figure in the history of the Kazakh Khanate in the 15th Century. Born around 1428, he became a ruler or 'khan' of the Kazakh Khanate, a role akin to a king. He ascended to the throne in 1511, ruling until 1523, and his reign is noted for establishing the Kazakh Khanate as a significant power in the region. Kasym Khan fostered political relationships with neighboring states and brought about a period of relative peace and stability. He is remembered for restructuring the khanate into 'jüz' or hordes to better manage the vast territory. He also played a pivotal role in reinforcing the Kazakh's nomadic horse riding culture. On the military front, Kasym Khan often defended his territory from the frequent attacks of the Uzbek Khanate. Furthermore, he promoted both Islamic and traditional Kazak values among his subjects. Despite his powerful position, little is known about his personal life. His significant contributions to Kazakh culture and analytics make him a revered figure in Kazakhstan's history.
sumy: He also played a pivotal role in reinforcing the Kazakh's nomadic horse riding culture.

base_text: Steve Lombardi is a former professional wrestler and wrestling executive hailing from Brooklyn, New York. He is well-known under his ring name, "The Brooklyn Brawler", and was employed by the World Wrestling Federation / Entertainment (now WWE) for over 30 years. He has also wrestled under other monikers, such as Kim Chee and Abe "Knuckleball" Schwartz. As the Brooklyn Brawler, Lombardi was often used as a jobber, meaning he frequently lost matches to bigger stars in order to build their character and popularity. Despite this, he managed to amass a considerable fan base because of his distinctive persona and on-screen talent. Apart from his in-ring career, Lombardi has also contributed behind the scenes, working as a road agent and helping to train future wrestling stars. His long tenure in the wrestling industry is testament to his versatility and dedication. Lombardi has truly left his mark in the world of professional wrestling, and the Brooklyn Brawler will always be remembered as a beloved WWE character. base_text: Resource monotonicity is a principle in cooperative game theory and economical decision-making. It refers to the idea that adding more resources or increasing the supply should never lead to a decrease in allocation for any player. In other words, if a collective resource pool increases, no individual's share should shrink as a result. That means any increase in total resources should improve or at least not worsen the situation of each participant. If a solution violates resource monotonicity, it's considered unfair or irrational since there's more to distribute but someone is getting less. This principle is usually used in economic and social systems to maintain stability and fairness. It is also often referenced in discussions around taxation and public goods. However, achieving resource monotonicity can be challenging due to conflicting interests. Nevertheless, its main goal is to maintain equitable treatment and prevent a paradoxical decrease in benefits in the face of increased resources.
sumy: Resource monotonicity is a principle in cooperative game theory and economical decision-making.

base_text: Pine Gap is a satellite surveillance base located near Alice Springs in the Northern Territory of Australia. base_text: An Address Point is a term often used in Geographic Information System (GIS) mapping. base_text: John Rogers Herbert was a noted British history and portrait painter of the 19th century. He was associated with the pre-Raphaelite movement, although his work displays a more classical style. Herbert was born in 1810 in the United Kingdom and, instead of attending art school, trained himself in painting. He initially earned recognition for his religious paintings, particular featuring biblical scenes. His work eventually caught the attention of Queen Victoria, who commissioned several pieces from him. Herbert's works are renowned for their attention to historical accuracy and detail. Notable paintings include "The First Introduction of Christianity into Britain" and "Our Saviour Subject to His Parents at Nazareth". In addition to painting, Herbert was also an active member of the Royal Academy of Arts. He was knighted in 1841 and passed away in 1890. Acraea oreas is a scientific name designated to a specific species of butterfly. These butterflies belong to the Nymphalidae family, which is one of the largest families of butterflies globally. Within this family, they fall in the Acraea genus, hinted by the first part of their name. 

The term 'oreas' signifies the butterfly's unique species within that genus. Known for their vibrant and distinctive wing patterns, these butterflies are usually found across various regions in Africa. They display sexual dimorphism, meaning male and female Acraea oreas have different appearances. 

Acraea oreas, like other butterflies, undergo a life cycle starting from egg to larvae, then pupa, and finally adulthood. The adult butterflies are primarily diurnal, meaning they are most active during the day. As for their diets, caterpillars often feed on a variety of plants while adult Acraea oreas feed on nectar.

base_text: The Haidarzadeh House refers to a historic residence located in Iran's East Azerbaijan Province in the city of Tabriz. It was a dwelling belonging to the Haidarzadeh family, a prominent and influential family in Iran with significant cultural and historical contributions. The house was primarily built during the Qajar era, reflecting the architecture and authentic Iranian designs from that time period. Its architecture includes a variety of elaborate designs, detailed painting, mirror work, and stained glass windows. Today, the Haidarzadeh House is a cultural and touristic attraction, having been turned into the Museum of Ostad Bohtouni, which is dedicated to showcasing the works of the Iranian master sculptor, Ostad Mohammad Ali Bohtouni. The museum contains a collection of sculptures, most of which were privately owned by the sculptor. The house's yard is filled with various statues, demonstrating the evolution of Bohtouni's work. The Haidarzadeh House therefore is not only of importance due to its historical and cultural significance, but also because it serves as a hub for art and history enthusiasts, with its current role as a museum. Being relatively well preserved, this house stands as a significant example of Qajar residential architecture. The Haidarzadeh House continues to fascinate visitors with its artistic, architectural, and historical features.

base_text: James Clayborne Jr. is a notable figure within the American political sphere, known primarily for his work within the Illinois State Senate. base_text: The boundary problem in spatial analysis refers to issues arising from the geographical limits imposed on studies. Essentially, it acknowledges that human activity and natural phenomena do not adhere to arbitrary borders used in research. This can cause distortions or biases in the results of spatial analysis. A common boundary problem is the Modifiable Areal Unit Problem (MAUP), where data change dramatically based on the size or layout of the area you've defined. It involves two main issues: scale and zoning or aggregation effects. The scale effect often refers to the level of detail at which analysis is done. For instance, analyzing data at a national level could yield very different results than at a city or neighborhood level. The zoning effect is concerned with how areas are grouped together, which can cause varying results as well. Boundary problems emphasize the importance of careful spatial definition in research. It shows that the study area selection can significantly influence the results in spatial analysis.
sumy: Essentially, it acknowledges that human activity and natural phenomena do not adhere to arbitrary borders used in research.

base_text: Cabo Rojo National Wildlife Refuge is a stunning natural reserve located in Cabo Rojo, Puerto Rico. It was established in 1974 by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service to protect migratory birds and their habitat. This refuge spans over 1,800 acres and offers a sanctuary for a variety of wildlife, including endangered species. Unique to this habitat are subtropical dry forests, which are considered globally endangered. These forests provide refuge for diverse species, such as the endangered Yellow-shouldered Blackbird. The refuge is also home to various kinds of flora, fauna, and a significant number of migratory birds. Visitors can experience bird watching, hiking and photography. With its unique ecosystems and species, Cabo Rojo National Wildlife Refuge is an important part of conservation efforts. It proves to be a significant place for scientists who carry out research to understand more about these unique habitats and their subdivisions. Overall, it serves as a crucial hub for wildlife preservation and environmental education in Puerto Rico.
sumy: These forests provide refuge for diverse species, such as the endangered Yellow-shouldered Blackbird.

base_text: Israel S. Dresner, often called "Izzy", was a prominent Rabbi and civil rights activist born in 1929. Dresner was a close associate of Martin Luther King Jr., and played a significant role in helping fight against racism and social inequality prevalent during that era. An example of his activism was the significant role he played in the organization of the "Interfaith Freedom Ride" in 1961, and he was subsequently arrested and jailed multiple times for his involvement in civil rights protests. Throughout his life, he used his position and influence within the Jewish community to rally support for racial equality. Until his retirement, Dresner also served as a Rabbi in several synagogues in New Jersey where he continued to advocate for social justice and equality. Even after his active period, Dresner's contribution to civil rights is widely recognized and respected. In slow phases, he pulled away from rabbinic duties to teach classes on social justice at many schools, including Rutgers University. Israel Dresner passed away in June 2021 but left behind a legacy of activism and fighting for civil rights. His life has been a testament to the fact that spiritual leaders can play a key role in fighting against social injustice.
sumy: Israel S. Dresner, often called "Izzy", was a prominent Rabbi and civil rights activist born in 1929.

base_text: Nowshera District is a significant administrative district located in the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa Province of Pakistan. It is about 27 miles from the capital city of Islamabad. Geographically, it is situated in the fertile and rich plains of the Peshawar Valley. Nowshera District is known for its military cantonments and the Pakistan Military Academy in the nearby town of Risalpur. Its eastern border lies along the banks of the Kabul River. The District is divided into 47 union councils for administrative purposes. It houses a diverse population with various tribes and languages, but Pashto is the primary spoken language. The district boasts various small and medium-sized industries concentrated in the Nowshera Industrial Estate. Historically, it was a crucial region due to its strategic location on the Grand Trunk Road, a major trade route. Nowshera continues to be significant for its military establishments and its contributions to Pakistan's economy and culture.

base_text: Experimental finance refers to the application of scientific experiments in the field of finance to understand and test theories and develop financial models. It uses methodologies derived from lab-controlled conditions to study behavioral patterns among investors, assess market dynamics, and determine potential outcomes of financial decisions. This approach overcomes the limitations of traditional theoretical financial analyses. In this, the participants make decisions in real or simulated economic contexts. The experiments can involve real money, incentivizing participants to reveal their true preferences and beliefs. Experimental finance can also study interactions in a market environment. Observational data gathered from these experiments is then used to validate or disprove the theories, and to gain insights into market operations. This field of study also contributes to policy-making by providing evidence-based results. Experimental finance encourages the development of more realistic models of financial markets. It is not only limited to understanding finance, but also includes areas such as accounting and corporate finance.
sumy: It uses methodologies derived from lab-controlled conditions to study behavioral patterns among investors, assess market dynamics, and determine potential outcomes of financial decisions.

base_text: The term "Tapete" is originated from the Portuguese and Spanish languages where it broadly means "rug" or "carpet". It can also be used metaphorically to refer to the flooring or foundation of something in certain contexts. A tapete may be used either for practical purposes like covering the floor or for decorative purposes to enhance interior aesthetics. They are generally placed in living rooms, bedrooms, or hallways. It's worth noting that the term "tapete" can also refer to the felt-covered surface of a gaming table, as in card games like poker. Finally, caring for a tapete often involves regular vacuuming and professional cleaning.

base_text: The National and University Library in Zagreb is the national library of Croatia and central library of the University of Zagreb. It was established in 1607 and it is one of the oldest institutions of its kind in Europe. It is located in a 15,755 square meter building in the center of Zagreb, the capital city of Croatia. The Library's primary mission is the preservation and dissemination of knowledge in the service of the public, the scientific, educational and cultural needs of the country. It holds more than 3 million items and, apart from books, the library's collection includes manuscripts, rare and old books, periodicals, and other library materials. The National and University Library also acts as the central library of the University’s faculties, academies, colleges, and institutes, providing acquisition, cataloging, and lending services. It plays a significant role in the promotion and development of Croatia’s print and electronic publishing industry. The Library is also a cultural institution hosting various exhibitions and public readings. As a heritage institution, it is involved in a range of international projects concerning the digitization of historical documents. It is recognized as one of the most important national cultural institutions with significant influence in the country's higher education system.
sumy: The Library is also a cultural institution hosting various exhibitions and public readings.

base_text: Ans van Kemenade is a renowned person in the field of linguistics, who hails from Netherlands. Her primary work is focused on theoretical linguistics with solemn emphasis on syntactic theory. Kemenade is particularly known for her significant contributions toward the understanding of historical syntax, specifically in Old and Middle English. She studied at the University of Amsterdam, where she was awarded her PhD in 1987. Her thesis was titled “Syntactic Case and Morphological Case in the History of English.” She is a professor of English linguistics at the Radboud University in Nijmegen in the Netherlands. Over the years, she has published many articles and a number of books on syntax and language change. Much of her research is based on combining data from modern and historical languages to develop theories of syntactic change. Her work has been influential in shaping the field of historical linguistics. Kemenade's intellectual devotion to linguistics has made her a well-respected figure among the community.
sumy: Ans van Kemenade is a renowned person in the field of linguistics, who hails from Netherlands.

base_text: Berlin Alexanderplatz is a large public square and transport hub located in the central Mitte district of Berlin, Germany. Named after Tsar Alexander I, it was originally a cattle market outside the city fortifications. Over time it became a commercial center, but was largely destroyed during World War II. In the 1960s, the square was redesigned as a pedestrian zone and has since become one of the city's most frequented shopping areas. In popular culture, Berlin Alexanderplatz is known worldwide due to Alfred Döblin's 1929 novel of the same name and Rainer Werner Fassbinder's 1980 14-hour film adaptation. The square is dominated by the Fernsehturm (TV Tower), a symbol of the city. Other prominent features include the World Time Clock and the Fountain of Friendship among Peoples. Alexanderplatz is one of the busiest transport intersections in Berlin, serving as a hub for trains, trams, buses, and the metro. It has a rich history and continues to be an iconic symbol of Berlin. Despite its modern appearance, it still retains elements of its past, making it a place where history and the present collide.
sumy: Named after Tsar Alexander I, it was originally a cattle market outside the city fortifications.

base_text: Jonathan Hazard was a prominent figure in the American Revolutionary War, particularly in Rhode Island, during the late 18th century. Born in 1756, he was from a historically significant family, the Hazards, who were among the first settlers in the state. More than just being a patriot, Jonathan Hazard was a delegate from Rhode Island to the Continental Congress in 1787 and 1788. Admittedly, he was less known for his contributions to the congress, and more for his strong anti-federalist opinions during the adoption of the U.S. Constitution. Hazard opposed centralized power and worked fervently to promote individual and state freedoms, believing these to be fundamental to a thriving republic. These stances made him a contentious figure overall, a notable voice among the Anti-Federalists. Post his political career, Hazard also dabbled in the study of medicine. He passed away in the year 1845. Throughout his life, Jonathan Hazard was a prolific advocate for the principles he believed in, an embodiment of the spirit of resistance during a critical era in American history. It is for these reasons, that Jonathan Hazard remains a part of American historical discourse.
sumy: Post his political career, Hazard also dabbled in the study of medicine.

base_text: A candle warmer is a household accessory that liquefies the wax of a candle without the need for a flame. It is designed for people who want to enjoy the scent of a candle without dealing with smoke or fire. A candle warmer works by using a heating element to slowly melt the candle. There are two common types: lamp style, which melts the candle from the top, and plate style, which sits underneath the candle and melts from the bottom up. By using a candle warmer, the lifespan of the candle can be greatly extended, since the wax is melted slowly, instead of being burnt by a flame. They are compact, easy to use, and can be placed in any part of the home. Many consider them to be a safer alternative to traditional candle burning. They can also be used with many different types of candles, regardless of shape or size. Some newer models have timers or temperature controls for added safety and convenience. As a bonus, keeping a candle warmer on can keep a room smelling great around-the-clock.
sumy: It is designed for people who want to enjoy the scent of a candle without dealing with smoke or fire.

base_text: Frøen Station is a railway station located on the west side of Oslo, Norway. This significant transport hub is found on the Oslo Metro's Holmenkollen Line and is situated between the stations of Steinerud and Ris. Named after Frøen, the residential neighborhood that surrounds it, it has been part of Oslo's public transportation network since 1898. Initially, it was used for steam trains, but it transitioned into a metro station when the line was electrified in 1912. Under the Oslo Metro system, it is known as station number 16. It has recently been renovated and currently has a wooden, vintage style structure. The station is elevated and offers a sweeping view of the North of Oslo. The station is unmanned but tickets can be bought at machines. It is regularly serviced by line 1 metro trains to and from the city center, making it a convenient location for passengers. It provides a valuable transport link within Oslo, connecting many suburban residents with the city.
sumy: Under the Oslo Metro system, it is known as station number 16.

base_text: Prajnalok Mahasthavir is a renowned figure in the Buddhist community, famous for being a significant contributor to the revival of Buddhism in India. He was born on 21st February 1901 and was originally named Ganganarayan Chaudhury. In the early stages of his life, he was heavily influenced by Hindu ideologies. However, following an encounter with an eminent Buddhist monk, he converted to Buddhism and became a monk himself. Spending much of his life studying and teaching Buddhism, he dedicated himself by establishing Buddhist temples and meditation centers not only in India but also around the globe. He also authored several important Buddhist literatures. His devotion to the religion led him to emphasize the importance of Pali, the conventional language of Theravada Buddhism, and he implemented measures to teach it in many key educational institutions in India. Prajnalok Mahasthavir passed away on 11th April 1979, leaving behind a great legacy in the field of Buddhist teachings. His efforts significantly contributed to the re-emergence of Buddhism in India during the 20th century. Today, his teachings continue to inspire followers of Buddhism around the world.

base_text: Vulcanoid is a term used in astronomy that refers to a hypothetical population of asteroids that could exist in a stable orbit within the Mercury's orbit. The term was derived from Vulcano, a planet proposed to exist in an orbit inside Mercury to explain certain peculiarities in Mercury's orbit but was eventually proven not to exist. However, the possibility of existence of small bodies or asteroids in this region hasn't been ruled out, hence the name Vulcanoids. These asteroids, if they exist, are expected to be located near the Sun and are therefore very difficult to observe due to the Sun's bright glare. Astronomers predict Vulcanoids to be between 100 meters to 60 kilometers in diameter. As of yet, despite intensive searches, no Vulcanoids have been discovered. If found, however, they could provide valuable information about the early solar system. They're widely believed to be remnants of the solar system's formation. Their study could potentially clarify theories about planet formation and the history of our solar system. As such, the quest to find these hypothesised asteroids continues even now.
sumy: If found, however, they could provide valuable information about the early solar system.

base_text: Eduard Birnbaum was a well-known German-Jewish cantor, musicologist and composer who was born in 1855 and passed away in 1920. He was a foremost authority within his field, championing Jewish liturgical music throughout the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Birnbaum was based in Königsberg, now Kaliningrad, Russia, where he served as an accomplished cantor for forty years. His monumental contribution to the field was the systematic collection and in-depth analysis of a wide range of traditional Jewish music across Europe. He was deeply devoted to the preservation and promotion of Jewish heritage in music. Moreover, he composed original music, and his works helped to inspire and influence future generations of cantors and Jewish musicologists. Birnbaum's immense archive of collected music is now housed at the Hebrew Union College in Cincinnati, Ohio, USA. He has been, and remains to this day, a pivotal figure in both the history of Judaism and the wider world of musicology. The term 'Eduard Birnbaum' is therefore synonymous with Jewish liturgical music and represents great dedication to the preservation of cultural musical heritage. His life's work provided considerable contributions to Jewish musicology and to the broader understanding of Jewish cultural history.
sumy: He was a foremost authority within his field, championing Jewish liturgical music throughout the late 19th and early 20th centuries.

base_text: Sarati is a form of writing system invented by J.R.R Tolkien, an English writer, poet, and philologist, best known for his high fantasy works like "The Lord of the Rings". base_text: The 2019 NHL Entry Draft was an event held by the National Hockey League (NHL), where teams from the league would select eligible players to join their ranks. The draft order was determined by a lottery system where teams that did not make the playoffs were given a chance to win a higher position. The 2019 NHL Entry Draft is regarded as one of the key ways in which teams within the NHL can build for their future.

base_text: The 1608th Air Transport Wing is a title used in reference to a defunct unit of the US Air Force. The Wing was founded in 1955 and was deactivated in 1966. base_text: Anton Dohrn was a prominent German biologist, zoologist, and marine biologist of the 19th century, known for his extensive contributions to invertebrate zoology and for promoting Darwinism. He was born in 1840 in Stettin, Prussia and showed an early interest in nature and science. He studied various subjects at different universities, but it was his engagement with Charles Darwin's 'Origin of species' that oriented him towards zoology. Dohrn advocated for a comparative approach in the study of embryology and morphology to understand evolutionary relationships. In 1872, he founded the Stazione Zoologica in Naples, Italy, the first research station designed for marine biology. His station became a model for marine laboratories worldwide and also a central hub for scientists to exchange ideas. Dohrn focused primarily on marine invertebrates and did extensive work on arachnids. He formulated the concept of 'Urform', a hypothetical ancestral form from which all animal phyla evolutionarily descends. Dohrn passed away in 1909, leaving a lasting legacy in biological research. His contributions have significantly shaped our understanding of marine biology and evolution.
sumy: He studied various subjects at different universities, but it was his engagement with Charles Darwin's 'Origin of species' that oriented him towards zoology.

base_text: Kufr or Kufeir is an Arabic term derived from the word "Kafara" which fundamentally translates to 'to cover up' or 'to hide'. However, in Islamic theology, it refers to 'disbelief' or 'unbelief'. Kufr is used to describe someone who rejects or disbelieves in God (Allah in the Islamic context) as described by Islam. This includes someone who denies or rejects any of the fundamental beliefs of Islam such as the Shahada (declaration of faith), belief in angels, the Qur'an, all the prophets, the Day of Judgment, and Divine Decree (destiny). Although, it's important to note the term can have varied uses and interpretations in different Islamic contexts. Someone who commits kufr is called a Kafir. A person may belong to another faith or might not affiliate with any religion, intending they reject the Islamic perspective of God. This may lead to them being classified as a Kafir. The term has also been historically used to designate non-Muslims with whom Muslims were at war. The term holds heavy connotations and is used sparingly, given its potential to cause offense.
sumy: Although, it's important to note the term can have varied uses and interpretations in different Islamic contexts.

base_text: The Oath of Maimonides is a traditional oath for doctors, originating from Jewish physician Maimonides. This oath presents an ethical code to be followed by those practicing medicine. It differs somewhat from the Hippocratic Oath traditionally taken by doctors, as it's more about ethical responsibility and respect towards teachers and fellow doctors than about individual patients. Its emphasis is on the moral responsibility of the doctor to treat patients with care and respect while increasing their own knowledge about medicine. The oath discourages doctors from engaging in unproven treatments, encourages seeking advice from other experts when needed, and acknowledges the limitations of medicine. The Oath of Maimonides is held in high regard by medical fraternities and is sometimes used in medical school graduation ceremonies. It highlights that medicine should be practiced with a sense of humility, humanity and a recognition of the divine aspect of healing. This oath effectively underscores the lofty goals and high moral standards to which physicians should aspire in their professional lives. Many physicians today see this oath as a timeless charter of medical ethics to uphold human dignity and sanctity of life. The Oath of Maimonides highlights the practitioners’ broader responsibility of sustaining the health and healing of the communities they serve.
sumy: This oath presents an ethical code to be followed by those practicing medicine.

base_text: The 1988 Kensington by-election was a political event in the United Kingdom that took place in the Kensington district of London. The result marked the first Conservative by-election gain from Labour since 1959. Despite the victory, the Conservative majority was significantly reduced from the previous general election. The 1988 Kensington by-election was widely seen as an important comment on Thatcher's popularity and government policies at that time. base_text: The Neutra VDL Studio and Residences, often simply referred to as the Neutra VDL House, is a notable architectural landmark located in Los Angeles, California. It was designed and built by the renowned architect Richard Neutra and his son Dion in 1966. This structure is particularly noteworthy for its unique use of glass and reflection, a prime example of Neutra's modernist style. The building is named "VDL" after Cees H. Van der Leeuw, a Dutch industrialist and philanthropist who funded its construction. The complex includes the family house, garden, and the studio where Richard Neutra did most of his design work. Fully restored in 2011, the Neutra VDL House now functions as a museum and is open to the public. Students and faculty from the College of Environmental Design at California State Polytechnic University, Pomona maintain the house. Various exhibitions and public events are held there, fostering a continued dialogue on architectural design. The site is also considered a research center, encouraging the advancement of architecture and design studies. Furthermore, it was designated as a National Historic Landmark in 2016.
sumy: The Neutra VDL Studio and Residences, often simply referred to as the Neutra VDL House, is a notable architectural landmark located in Los Angeles, California.

base_text: The Lucy poems are a series of five verses written by the English Romantic poet William Wordsworth during the late 18th and early 19th century. These poems focus on the poet's love for a girl named Lucy who dies young. Lucy is portrayed as a symbol of natural beauty and innocent life, and her untimely death is viewed as a heartbreaking loss of purity and simplicity. The poems are written in first person, reflecting Wordsworth's personal feelings and experiences. These poems are known for their simple and natural language, which was revolutionary in a time when poetry was characterized by ornate and artificial language. The five poems in the series are "Strange fits of passion have I known", "She dwelt among the untrodden ways", "I travelled among unknown men", "Three years she grew in sun and shower", and "A slumber did my spirit seal". The Lucy poems are considered one of Wordsworth's most important contributions to English poetry. Some critics view Lucy as a fictional character, a creation of the poet's imagination, while others believe she represents a real person in Wordsworth's life. What's consistent across all interpretations is that through Lucy, Wordsworth is able to deeply explore themes of love, nature, and death.
sumy: These poems focus on the poet's love for a girl named Lucy who dies young.

base_text: The Metro D Line, originally known as the Purple Line, is a public transit rail service operated by the Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority (LACMTA) in Los Angeles, California. base_text: Alice Weidel is a well-known German politician affiliated with the Alternative for Germany (AfD) party. Born in 1979, she is renowned for her financial savvy and conservative views. base_text: Egyptian Revival decorative arts is a style of design that draws inspiration from the art, architecture, and culture of ancient Egypt. This style emerged in the late 18th and early 19th centuries, sparked by Napoleon's campaign in Egypt and the accompanying scientific study of ancient Egyptian remains. The style is characterized by the use of ancient Egyptian motifs, such as sphinxes, obelisks, and hieroglyphics. The objects featured ornate designs with intertwined figures of birds, snakes, and various mythological creatures. The Egyptian Revival movement was not limited to artifacts and jewelry, it was evident in architecture as well with pyramid-shaped structures becoming popular. This movement primarily took root in Europe and North America and impacted almost every facet of decorative art including furniture, ceramics, and textiles. It was also a popular style used in the design of public buildings, monuments, and residential architecture. This style has seen resurgences periodically, with notable peaks in the early and mid-20th century. Today, Egyptian Revival decorative arts are treasured as period pieces showing a unique fusion of Western and Egyptian aesthetics. As a whole, this design style is globally recognized and celebrated for its distinct elements.
sumy: The objects featured ornate designs with intertwined figures of birds, snakes, and various mythological creatures.
