base_text: St Bride's Church, Llansantffraed is a historical place of worship located in Llansantffraed, Breconshire, Wales. The church is dedicated to Saint Bridget, an Irish saint, and is part of the diocese of Swansea and Brecon in the Church in Wales. It is a Grade II listed building, a status which denotes that it is of special architectural or historic interest. The exact date of its construction is unknown, but it is believed to date back to at least the 14th century. The current structure follows a classic medieval design and some of its original features like a west bell-cote and a 16th-century south porch are still intact. The church had major restoration during the 19th century which included the rebuilding of its chancel. The church's bell, inscribed with the year 1679, is believed to be one of the oldest in the area. The cemetery surrounding the church hosts a collection of historic headstones. The interior of the church hosts a notable stained glass window and houses an ancient font. Overall, St Bride's Church is a valuable part of Welsh history and heritage, serving as a symbol of the country's religious past.

base_text: Júnior Urso, whose full name is José Rodrigo Bento da Silva Júnior, is a Brazilian professional footballer. base_text: Weinan is a prefecture-level city found in the eastern part of Shaanxi province, China. It covers an area of about 13,000 square kilometers. It borders the provincial capital of Xi'an to the West and is home to over 5 million people. Historically, Weinan has been a significant location, especially as a transportation and trade center. It was critical in the ancient Silk Road connecting China with the West. Today, Weinan boasts a variety of cultural sites and natural attractions. It is famous for its wine production industry, which gave it its name 'Weinan,' literally translating as 'wine south.' It is also home to the renowned Huashan Mountain, one of China's five sacred mountains. Weinan is diverse in its ethnic composition and offers a unique blend of traditional and modern cultures. The city has significant influence in the industries of tourism, manufacturing, and education.

base_text: BX convoys were a series of convoys run during World War II to help combat the threat of German U-boats in the Atlantic. These convoys were established as a response to the intensity of the Battle of the Atlantic, where German forces sought to block aid sent from America to Britain. The term BX convoy stands for Boston Crosstown, signifying the convoys’ route from Boston, USA to Halifax, Nova Scotia in Canada. This was a shorter, safer path than the North Atlantic route, which was heavily targeted by German forces. Evolved from the BHX Convoy, BX convoys allowed slower merchant ships to travel at their own pace, reducing the risk of submarine attacks. At Halifax, individual ships from several BX convoys were grouped into larger, faster convoys to cross the Atlantic. From September 1940 to May 1941, these convoys ran twice weekly. They were crucial in maintaining supply lines and providing necessary logistical support during the war. Despite being a smaller operation than other convoy systems, BX convoys played a strategic role in beating the German naval blockade. In total, over 500 merchant ships made the journey to the Atlantic via BX convoys.
sumy: BX convoys were a series of convoys run during World War II to help combat the threat of German U-boats in the Atlantic.

base_text: The Bluebonnet Ordnance Plant was a U.S. military facility that was established during World War II. The plant was located in McGregor, Texas and covered an area of about 10,000 acres. It was primarily dedicated to producing munitions and explosive products for the military. Facilities like this were vital to support the American war effort, supplying troops with the necessary equipment. The Bluebonnet plant manufactured bomb loading devices and artillery ammunition among other products. Many women were recruited to work at the plant due to labor shortages, in what had traditionally been male roles. After the war ended, the plant was closed down and the facilities were sold off. The former site of the Bluebonnet Ordnance Plant, however, was later repurposed and now forms part of the McGregor Industrial Park. Despite its relatively short period of operation, the Bluebonnet Ordnance Plant played a significant role in wartime manufacturing. Today, it remains as a symbol of the national mobilization during World War II.
sumy: The plant was located in McGregor, Texas and covered an area of about 10,000 acres.

base_text: Day County was a political subdivision that existed in the U.S state of Oklahoma from 1892 to 1907. It was created during the period when Oklahoma was still an organized territory, before it became a state. The county was named after Charles Day, a well-known rancher and economist of the time. It was established by the Organic Act on May 2, 1890, and operationalized two years later. The county spanned an area that included present-day Ellis, Woodward, Dewey, and into Major County. It was served by a single government seat located in Grand or Day City. However, along with other Oklahoma territories, Day County ceased to exist after the statehood. It was dissolved and divided into four counties, namely Ellis, Harper, Woodward, and Woods when Oklahoma became a state on November 16, 1907. The dissolution of Day County was based on its population, as its distribution was imbalanced. This led the framers of the constitution to divide Day County into smaller and more proportionate counties.
sumy: Day County was a political subdivision that existed in the U.S state of Oklahoma from 1892 to 1907.

base_text: Rui Naiwei is a Chinese professional Go player who became notable not only for her expertise in Go but also for challenging gender norms in the traditionally male-dominated world of the board game. Born in March 1963 in Shanghai, China, she started learning Go at a young age and turned professional at the age of 17. Rui became the first woman to enter the top tier of competitive Go, shattering glass ceilings. She won her first world championship in 1991 and won many national and international titles thereafter. In 1999, Rui moved to South Korea and achieved further recognition, becoming one of the most accomplished Go players in the world. Today, she remains a powerful figure in the Go game community and is a symbol of inspiration for many female Go players around the world. Despite facing significant challenges, Rui Naiwei carved her way not just as a top player, but as the trailblazer for gender equality within the board game industry. base_text: The Walhalla railway line is a notable historical landmark located in Victoria, Australia. Once an actively functioning train line, it was originally built in the early 20th century in order to facilitate the transport of goods and people to and from the gold mining town of Walhalla. The development of the line was a significant project, traversing some challenging terrains including rugged mountains. It commenced operation in 1910. However, the Walhalla gold field's unexpectedly rapid decline led to the line becoming unprofitable. Consequently, the Walhalla railway line was decommissioned in 1954 and most of the track infrastructure was removed. These days, it is a place of historical interest and a small section of the former line has been restored as the Walhalla Goldfields Railway, operating as a tourist attraction. The line operates a daily heritage service between Thomson and Walhalla. Today, the Walhalla railway line represents an important part of Australia's gold rush heritage. Visitors can ride on the scenic railway and learn about its rich history.
sumy: The Walhalla railway line is a notable historical landmark located in Victoria, Australia.

base_text: Ghaffor Mirzoyev is a former Tajikistani politician and military officer, prominent for his role in the civil war of Tajikistan when he led the opposition forces during the 1990s. From 1995 to 2004, he served as the Chairman of Tajikistan's State Committee for National Security, equivalent to a head of the intelligence service. His influence, however, declined after the death of his main political patron, President Emomali Rahmon, and he was eventually charged with and convicted of corruption. Mirzoyev was jailed in 2004 but was granted a presidential pardon in 2012. His life and career have been marked by political turbulence and controversy. Despite his past, he remains a figure of significance in understanding Tajikistan's recent history.

base_text: The 152 mm howitzer M1938 (M-10) is a type of Soviet artillery weapon used mainly during World War II. It was first produced in 1939 after most of the 1930s was spent improving its design. base_text: Jan Baalsrud was a Norwegian resistance fighter during World War II. He was the sole survivor of a failed sabotage mission by the Norwegian resistance against the Nazis. base_text: The Beef Bones Regulations 1997 is a legislation implemented by the UK government in response to the BSE (Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy) crisis, known as the "mad cow disease." The regulations prohibited the use of bones from cattle aged over 30 months for consumption by humans. This was because BSE was found to concentrate in the bones, making them a potential transmission source for variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (vCJD), a deadly neurological disease in humans. The law applied to all establishments preparing meat, including butchers, supermarkets, and restaurants. Meat must have all remnants of spinal cord removed, while the skull, brain, eyes, and tonsils must also be excluded from the food chain. In 2001, the 1997 regulations were supplemented by The TSE (England) Regulations, enhancing meat hygiene controls and waste disposal measures. The Beef Bones Regulations 1997 were eventually repealed in 2006 as the BSE risk had significantly reduced. However, rigorous surveillance and stringent controls remain in place to prevent any similar future crises in the beef industry. It's an important example of how governments must respond to public health crises related to the food supply.
sumy: This was because BSE was found to concentrate in the bones, making them a potential transmission source for variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (vCJD), a deadly neurological disease in humans.

base_text: The Meidob volcanic field is an expansive volcanic region located in North Darfur, Sudan. Covering an area of about 5,000 square kilometers, it is among the largest volcanic fields within the country. It is characterized by numerous basaltic cinder cones and the 140 kilometer long lava flow called Arrousa lava. The field owes its formation to the intense volcanic activity that took place in the region during the Holocene Epoch, specifically in the Neolithic period. The last known eruption reportedly occurred around 3000 BC, leaving the field currently dormant. Evidence of human habitation has been found in the area, including megalithic structures known as "taulas". Despite being a relatively less-studied region, the field is significant for understanding the volcanic history of Sudan. Its volcanic structures, ancient lava flows, and remnants of human settlements provide a valuable resource for archeological and geological research. Proximity to the Marra Mountains, another prominent volcanic area, highlights the region's volcanic past. Today, the field is a focus of study for those interested in volcanic fields and the history of human-geological interaction.
sumy: Evidence of human habitation has been found in the area, including megalithic structures known as "taulas".

base_text: Ergaticus is derived from the term "ergative", which, in linguistics, refers to a certain type of language construction where the object of a transitive verb and the subject of an intransitive verb are treated in the same way, while the subject of a transitive verb is treated differently. The term "Ergaticus" specifically is often used in taxonomy, the science of classifying living organisms. In this context, Ergaticus is a genus of bird in the family Parulidae (New World warblers). This genus contains two species, the red warbler and the pink-headed warbler, both of which are native to North and Central America. These birds are known for their vibrant colors and distinct songs. In summary, Ergaticus is both a term linked to a linguistic concept around verb use, and the name of a genus of brightly-colored, song-filled warblers. Research or expert guidance is necessary to understand whether the term is being used in a linguistic or biological context.

base_text: Minotaur IV is a type of space launch vehicle, specifically designed to send small payloads into outer space. It is part of the Minotaur series of rockets developed by Orbital Sciences Corporation, now part of Northrop Grumman. Minotaur IV was first launched in 2010 and it primarily uses the decommissioned components of the Peacekeeper Intercontinental Ballistic Missiles (ICBMs). The rocket is approximately 24 meters tall and has three solid-fueled stages for flight. It has been successfully used for numerous space launches, deploying both military satellites and scientific instruments into space. With its specific design, Minotaur IV proves to be an effective and reliable option for launching small and medium-sized payloads. Besides, the policy of utilizing decommissioned ICBMs helps in promoting sustainable practices in space technology. Indeed, the Minotaur IV embodies both technological progress and sustainability.
sumy: The rocket is approximately 24 meters tall and has three solid-fueled stages for flight.

base_text: The National Physicians Alliance (NPA) is a non-profit organization that was formed by physicians in the United States. Established in 2005, it aimed to create a network of health-care professionals committed to the core values of the medical profession, primarily the principles of service, integrity, and advocacy. The NPA was driven by the ethos of promoting quality health care for all, regardless of the individual's capacity to pay. The organization focused on delivering high medical standards and ensuring the patient's well-being is at the heart of all health-related decisions. NPA provided a platform for healthcare professionals to engage and shape public policy concerning national health issues. They fostered the idea of evidence-based prescribing as well. base_text: Ein HaMifratz is a term in Hebrew that translates in English to 'The Bay.' It's most commonly associated with Kishon River's estuary in the Haifa Bay of Israel. base_text: Belgian Mexicans are people of Belgian descent who were born in, or currently live in, Mexico. Initially, the Belgian community in Mexico was quite small, but over time it has grown and Belgian Mexicans have spread throughout the country. The culture and traditions of Belgium are maintained within this community, alongside their adopted Mexican culture. base_text: Ürjingiin Yadamsüren is a significant name in Mongolian history, known for his contribution to literature, poetry, and translation work. base_text: Charron Island, also known as Île Charron, is a small island located in the province of Quebec, Canada. Specifically, it sits in the Saint Lawrence River, in the eastern part of Montreal suburb. The island is part of the Hochelaga Archipelago, which includes around 234 islands, including the Island of Montreal. Charron Island is best known as the location of the Parc de l'Île-Charron, a large park that is popular for outdoor recreational activities such as hiking, cycling, picnicking, and bird watching. Despite its economy driven mostly by tourism, Charron Island maintains its natural appeal, providing a serene escape from the bustling city life.

base_text: The Gymnasium Carolinum in Osnabrück, Germany, is a prestigious educational institution known for its long history. It was founded around the year 804 by Charles the Great, making it one of the oldest schools, if not the oldest, currently in operation in the world. The school's name, Carolinum, is derived from Carolus Magnus, the Latin name of the founder, Charles the Great. The Gymnasium Carolinum is a secondary school that follows the German Gymnasium school system, comparable to high school or grammar school in English-speaking countries, but with a strong emphasis on academic learning. This institution caters to students from grade five up to the Abitur, the university-qualifying examination. Its curriculum includes Latin, sciences, social sciences, languages, arts, music and more. While it upholds traditional educational elements, it also incorporates progressive methods to support the holistic development of students. Over the centuries, it has undergone several changes and advancements fitting its status as a comprehensive educational institution. The school is also known for its historic edifice with architectural features that have cultural and historical significance. Despite modern challenges, the Carolinum continues to maintain its unique character besides nurturing inquisitive minds.
sumy: The Gymnasium Carolinum in Osnabrück, Germany, is a prestigious educational institution known for its long history.

base_text: Nikolai Gerasimenko is a well-known figure in the scientific community, specifically in the field of space exploration. Born in Russia, he is a renowned Russian astronomer. Not only was he responsible for the discovery and observation of numerous celestial bodies, but his work has contributed significantly to space research. One of his most significant contributions is the discovery of the comet 67P/Churyumov–Gerasimenko, which was named after him and Klim Ivanovych Churyumov. This comet gained international fame when it was visited by the European Space Agency's Rosetta Mission in 2014. This was of special significance as it provided vital insights about the formation of the solar system. Throughout his career, Gerasimenko's expertise and insights have earned him substantial prestige in his field. He remains an enduring key figure in the world of astronomy and space exploration. The term "Nikolai Gerasimenko" therefore symbolizes significant contribution and dedication in the field of astronomical research.
sumy: Not only was he responsible for the discovery and observation of numerous celestial bodies, but his work has contributed significantly to space research.

base_text: János Konrád was a Hungarian author, journalist, and translator, best known for his significant contributions to 20th-century Hungarian literature. base_text: Kyō ware refers to a type of Japanese pottery that was traditionally made in the Kyoto city's Gojo-zaka area. They often incorporate the beauty of nature, involving flowers, birds, and scenes from traditional literature in their designs. Kyō ware exhibits a balance between the rich traditions of the past and contemporary aesthetics. They are appreciated as works of art, in addition to their practical uses.

base_text: The William Jerome I House is a historical site in Colorado, United States. It was built in 1889 and is named after the famous Jerome family. base_text: Yunnan Zhuang customs and culture refer to the traditional customs, practices, and way of life of the Zhuang people living in Yunnan, a province in southern China. The Zhuang are known for their colorful folk songs and dances, along with their intricate brocade weaving and embroidery. Their dietary practices mostly include rice and pickled dishes, with a distinctive use of sour flavors. The Zhuang traditional religion includes elements of ancestor worship and nature spirits. Architecture in Zhuang culture is often characterized by wood, with stilt houses being especially common. Overall, Yunnan Zhuang customs and culture provide a rich tapestry of traditions that greatly enrich China's cultural diversity.

base_text: Cabal Online is a massively multiplayer online role-playing game (MMORPG) that was first released in 2005 in South Korea. It was developed by a South Korean company called ESTsoft. base_text: "Death Is My Trade" is a phrase popularly recognized as the title of a novel written by Robert Merle. This intense work of literature depicts the life of an SS officer, Rudolf Höss, who commanded Auschwitz, the most notorious Nazi concentration camp during World War II. The novel provides a stark examination of the mechanization of mass murder, effectively underscored by the deceptively regular life of the protagonist. It is told from the perspective of the camp commandant, who sees death and extermination as his duty and profession, thereby connecting to the title "Death Is My Trade". A grim exploration of the human capacity for evil, the phrase embodies the cold, detached business of systematic genocide. It is a chilling reminder of a historical era characterized by profound inhumanity, where death was literally traded en masse. The phrase can also be seen as a metaphor for any profession or practice that deals extensively with mortality and killing.
sumy: This intense work of literature depicts the life of an SS officer, Rudolf Höss, who commanded Auschwitz, the most notorious Nazi concentration camp during World War II.

base_text: The Competition (Jersey) Law 2005 is a legislative framework introduced in the island of Jersey to promote healthy competition among businesses and discourage anti-competitive behavior. This law primarily covers two aspects, cartels and monopolies. Cartels are agreements between firms to control prices, which is prohibited under this law to prevent any group from dominating the market. Monopolies, where a single firm holds total control over an entire market, are also restricted, as they prevent other businesses from competing fairly. The law also aims to eliminate any manipulation that prevents or reduces consumer choice within the market. Under the auspices of this law, the Jersey Competition Regulatory Authority (JCRA) can investigate businesses suspected of breaching this legislation and has the power to impose financial penalties. The JCRA can similarly review and approve mergers and acquisitions to ensure they do not lead to a significant lessening of competition. Furthermore, businesses can approach the JCRA for advice on whether their actions might contravene the legislation. The ultimate aim of the Competition (Jersey) Law 2005 is to protect consumer welfare and ensure economic efficiency.
sumy: The Competition (Jersey) Law 2005 is a legislative framework introduced in the island of Jersey to promote healthy competition among businesses and discourage anti-competitive behavior.

base_text: Upflow anaerobic sludge blanket digestion, often abbreviated as UASB, is a treatment method used for wastewater. The concept utilizes an anaerobic process, meaning it operates without oxygen. This method tends to be used in wastewater treatment facilities to effectively break down waste and purify the water. The process operates in a UASB reactor, where wastewater flows from the bottom to the top, against a blanket of sludge. The sludge is composed of bacterial substances which assist in decomposing the waste in water. As wastewater passes through the sludge blanket, organic matter gets converted into biogas by the microorganisms. This biogas rises to the top and is collected, which can then be used as an energy source. The purified water is separated from the sludge and leaves from the top of the reactor. The sludge settles down to be reused. This technique is energy-efficient, cost-effective, and reduces air pollution due to its capture and use of methane gas.
sumy: Upflow anaerobic sludge blanket digestion, often abbreviated as UASB, is a treatment method used for wastewater.

base_text: The term "Crumpets" refers to a popular type of griddle cake typically consumed in the United Kingdom and other countries with British influence. base_text: The Rally of Republican Lefts is a political concept that originates from France. It refers to a center-left political coalition that was formed in 1949 in the Fourth French Republic. The main objectives of the Rally of Republican Lefts were to combat communist influence and preserve the democratic process within the country. Despite having 'Republican' in its name, it stands for left wing policies as opposed to the American understanding of 'Republican'. It played a key role in shaping France's political landscape after World War II. By 1956, however, the coalition had dispersed due to internal differences. base_text: James Edgar was an innovative Scottish entrepreneur in the 19th century beloved for his impact on American Christmas traditions. base_text: Vilyuy is the name of a river located in Siberia, Russia. As the longest tributary of the Lena River, it spans approximately 2,650 kilometers. base_text: Spondyloarthropathy refers to a group of inflammatory diseases that involve both the joints and the entheses (the points where the ligaments and tendons attach to bones). It predominantly affects the spine, though other joints can also be involved. Some common examples of these conditions include ankylosing spondylitis, reactive arthritis, psoriatic arthritis, and arthritis related to inflammatory bowel diseases like Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis. The exact cause is unknown but these diseases are believed to have a genetic predisposition. Symptoms vary based on the type and individual, but generally include back pain, joint pain and swelling, and stiffness. A key feature of these diseases is inflammation, which can lead to permanent damage if left untreated. Therefore, early diagnosis and treatment are crucial. Treatments depend on the specific type and may include medication, physical therapy, and in some cases surgery. It's a chronic condition, meaning it persists over a long period of time, although symptoms may come and go. Spondyloarthropathy can affect people of all ages, but often begins in late adolescence and early adulthood.

base_text: The Ulysses S. Grant Memorial is a presidential memorial in Washington D.C., honoring Ulysses S. base_text: Lake McLarty is a body of water located in Western Australia, specifically to the south of Perth. base_text: "Transformations" is an opera composed by American composer Conrad Susa. The work finds inspiration from a collection of Grimm's Fairy Tales as interpreted by twentieth-century poet Anne Sexton who published a compilation of her dark, modern versions of these traditional stories under the same title. Premiered in 1973 by the Minnesota Opera, "Transformations" features a novel approach: It integrates spoken dialogue and a chamber music ensemble instead of employing a full-sized symphony orchestra. The opera consists of ten well-known fairy tale transformations, including Rumpelstiltskin, Briar Rose, and Snow White, among others. The opera's narrative is more about Sexton's personal transformation and journey through mental illness than the fairy tales themselves. These tales serve as metaphors for the poet's lived experiences. The libretto is largely direct quotes from Sexton's poems adding depth to the characters while challenging the conventions of traditional opera. The stories are interwoven, with characters shifting between roles across the tales. Dark, complex, and emotionally heavy, "Transformations" is a unique blend of music, drama, and modern verse that reimagines the boundaries of the opera genre.
sumy: "Transformations" is an opera composed by American composer Conrad Susa.

base_text: The Geology of Kentucky is the study of rocks, minerals, landscapes, and the processes that have created its landforms over billions of years. The state is divided into five primary regions, each with distinct geological features: the Cumberland Plateau, the Bluegrass region, the Pennyroyal Plateau, the Western Coal Fields, and the Jackson Purchase. The Cumberland Plateau, in the easternmost part of the state, is noted for its rugged terrain and coal deposits. The Bluegrass Region is characterized by rich soil formed from limestone bedrock, perfect for pastureland. To the west, the Pennyroyal Plateau is filled with sinkholes and caverns due to its karst landscape, created by the dissolution of soluble rocks. The Western Coal Fields, as the name implies, is known for considerable coal reserves. The Jackson Purchase in the far west of Kentucky has a flat terrain of rich, fertile soil, unlike the other regions. The state's geology also includes a rich array of fossils, including those of early marine life present in the Paleozoic era. Formation of these geologic features has occurred over billions of years, from tectonic, erosional, and depositional processes. Thus, the geology of Kentucky tells the story of the state's vibrant geologic past and plays a crucial role in its natural resources and landscape features.

base_text: The Gurindji people are an Indigenous Australian group located traditionally in the Victoria River region of the Northern Territory in Australia. base_text: A biosurfactant is a type of surfactant produced by living organisms, typically microorganisms like bacteria, fungi, and yeasts. There were also naval displays, with around a dozen nations sending warships. The idea was not just to commemorate the past, but also to emphasize America's growth and bright future. Despite its significance, the Jamestown Exposition suffered from financial issues and did not turn a profit. However, the site of the exposition later became the Norfolk Naval Base. The Jamestown Exposition served as a significant event encapsulating a blend of homage to the historical past and a projection of future potential.
sumy: There were also naval displays, with around a dozen nations sending warships.

base_text: Cracking joints is a common practice among people, where a popping or cracking sound is produced by bending, twisting, or pulling on certain body parts. This typically happens in the knuckles, neck, back, and sometimes in the knees, wrists, ankles, and other joints. The exact reason behind this is not fully understood, however, it is generally believed to be harmless. It's thought to be caused by the release of gas bubbles trapped in your joints, or from tendons and ligaments snapping over tissues because of minor adjustments in their positioning. You can often feel a sense of relief after the joint is cracked, leading many people to make a habit out of it. Despite various theories, there is no scientific evidence that associates joint cracking with arthritis or other joint issues. However, forcefully cracking joints, or doing it too frequently, can injure the ligaments around the joints and should be avoided. Despite common beliefs, it is not harmful and should not cause pain. If cracking is accompanied by pain or swelling, it might signify an underlying medical condition that needs attention. Therefore, if joint cracking is uncomfortable or causing concern, it is advisable to seek medical advice.
sumy: Cracking joints is a common practice among people, where a popping or cracking sound is produced by bending, twisting, or pulling on certain body parts.

base_text: Rasul Amin is a term derived from Arabic, used within Islamic tradition. It loosely translates to "the trustworthy messenger". The term has significant reverence in Islam because it is usually attributed to the Prophet Muhammad. Because Muhammad is considered the final messenger of Islam's Allah, being described as "trustworthy" holds immense importance. This represents his character which was known for honesty and integrity. It suggests that Muhammad was trusted by Allah to deliver the divine revelations correctly. Notwithstanding, it also reflects how he is viewed by the Muslim community - that is, a reliable and credible source of religious guidance. Additionally, it is a testament to how he lived his life, setting the benchmark of moral conduct for Muslims. Therefore, 'Rasul Amin' encapsulates the role and character of the Prophet Muhammad within Islam.
sumy: Because Muhammad is considered the final messenger of Islam's Allah, being described as "trustworthy" holds immense importance.

base_text: The term 2013 FIBA Americas Championship refers to the regional basketball tournament held in 2013 for the Americas region, under the auspices of the International Basketball Federation (FIBA). This tournament took place in Caracas, Venezuela from August 30 to September 11, 2013. This was the top-level championship for basketball national teams in Americas, and was the qualifying tournament for the 2014 FIBA World Cup in Spain. The competition attracted men's national teams from across the Americas, including powerhouse basketball nations like USA, Brazil, and Argentina. Mexico won the tournament, achieving its first ever FIBA Americas Championship title. This event involved a round-robin preliminary round followed by a single-elimination round to determine the winner. The top four teams in the tournament earned a spot in the 2014 FIBA World Cup. The FIBA Americas Championship is an important tournament in international basketball and the 2013/version was particularly memorable.
sumy: This tournament took place in Caracas, Venezuela from August 30 to September 11, 2013.

base_text: Rodríguez is an Hispanic surname which has its roots in Spain and is one of the most common surnames in the Spanish-speaking world. The origin comes from the Germanic name 'Hrodrick', meaning 'famous power'. It was later adopted and altered by the Spanish during the middle ages. The term is patronymic in nature, meaning it's derived from the father's name. Rodríguez signifies 'son of Rodrigo'. Rodrigo, means 'famous ruler', thus Rodríguez represents an extension of a lineage of 'famous rulers'. Like many Hispanic surnames, Rodríguez would typically be used in conjunction with a maternal surname. It's spread globally due to colonization and migration. Famous individuals such as Alex Rodriguez, the American baseball player, also bear this surname. Being prevalent in Spanish-speaking countries, it's often associated with Latino identity.
sumy: Like many Hispanic surnames, Rodríguez would typically be used in conjunction with a maternal surname.

base_text: Cladoniaceae is a family of lichens, which are composite organisms that arise from algae or cyanobacteria living among fungi in a symbiotic relationship. Lichens in this family are usually characterized by the production of a branched, upright or hanging thallus. The Cladoniaceae family includes some of the most familiar and widely recognized lichens, such as reindeer moss. It is globally distributed and can be found from the Arctic to the equator, but are most commonly found in boreal forests and tundra habitats. They play key roles in these ecosystems, providing a food source for animals and contributing to soil formation. There are several hundred recognized species within the Cladoniaceae family. They can be observed growing on rocks, soil, mosses, tree barks, and wood. They exhibit a great variety of growth forms, including fruticose (bushy), foliose (leafy), and squamulose (consisting of small scales). Because of their sensitivity to air pollution, their presence and health can serve as indicators of environmental quality. In addition, some species of Cladoniaceae have traditional uses in medicine and dye production.
sumy: Lichens in this family are usually characterized by the production of a branched, upright or hanging thallus.

base_text: World Embryo is a term used predominantly in a graphical novel (manga) context, more specifically referring to a Japanese manga series authored by Daisuke Moriyama. base_text: Ari Wallach is a renowned American entrepreneur, futurist, and strategist. He is the CEO and founder of Synthesis Corp., a strategic consultancy firm that assists leaders, teams, and organizations to determine their long-term future in innovative and sustainable ways. Wallach is also the founder of Longpath Labs, a project aimed at cultivating long-term thinking and ethical frameworks in decision-making processes. His work essentially involves helping people and organizations to think ahead and make strategic decisions based on future possibilities. Wallach also works extensively in social innovation, policymakers, and is an adjunct professor at the University of Pennsylvania. Wallach’s extensive work in striving for future sustainability has made him a unique figure in futurism. base_text: The Hubble European Space Agency Information Centre is an organization that provides detailed information and updates about the Hubble Space Telescope. Established by the European Space Agency (ESA), this centre supports one of the largest and most versatile space observatories in the world. It offers resources for scientists, educators, news media and the public to learn more about the telescope's significant discoveries. This centre also provides high-resolution images taken by the telescope, as well as scientific data for researchers. Notably, the ESA is one of the main partners in the Hubble Space Telescope project, along with NASA. Therefore, this Information Centre plays a crucial role in broadening our understanding of space, stars, galaxies, and other celestial bodies. It allows people worldwide to stay informed about the Hubble's mission and the remarkable insights it continues to reveal about our universe. In addition to providing information, the Hubble European Space Agency Information Centre also assists in coordinating European contributions to the Hubble project. sumy: Therefore, this Information Centre plays a crucial role in broadening our understanding of space, stars, galaxies, and other celestial bodies.

base_text: Panaramitee Style refers to distinctive Aboriginal rock art found in Australia, particularly in the Central Australian region. This style of art is traditionally characterized by simple, geometric designs. Unlike some forms of Aboriginal art that incorporate human or animal figures, the Panaramitee style mainly utilizes symbols such as circles, lines, and dots. The art was often created by engraving into rock surfaces which left an indelible mark, preserving the work. It is believed to be one of the oldest forms of rock art in the world. Anthropologists have suggested that the artists might have had a practical as well as symbolic reasons for placing the petroglyphs where they did. The Panaramitee Style is usually associated with desert areas. Its name comes from Panaramitee Station in South Australia where this style was first recognized and studied by researchers. Today, examples of Panaramitee Style art can be found across much of the Australian continent. It plays a significant role in understanding early human civilization in Australia.
sumy: This style of art is traditionally characterized by simple, geometric designs.

base_text: Andreas Eudaemon-Joannis, often referred to as Andrew Eudaemon-John, was a renowned figure in the world of philosophy and divinity from the 16th century. He was born in the year 1520 and passed away in 1582, making his noteworthy contributions mostly during the Renaissance era. Being Greek in origin, his true name was Andreas Ioannides which was later Latinized as Andreas Eudaemon-Joannis. He served as a professor at the University of Paris where he chiefly focused on Greek and Latin languages. His scholarly work typically revolved around interpreting Aristotle's works, alongside contributing to nominalistic theology. He is well-known for his reviews and deliberations on "Physics" and "On the Heavens", two of Aristotle's most influential pieces. His interpretations were marked by a distinct pragmatic methodology. This unique approach rendered him as one of the key figures who bridged the gap between Medieval Scholastic Aristotelianism and Renaissance Aristotelianism. His insights have left an enduring legacy on 16th-century philosophy, specifically in rationality debates. To this day, his works remain as a significant reference for philosophers and scholars studying Aristotelian interpretations.
sumy: His scholarly work typically revolved around interpreting Aristotle's works, alongside contributing to nominalistic theology.

base_text: Sumitra Guha is a renowned Indian classical singer, who specializes in Hindustani classical music. Born in Kolkata, she started her musical journey at a very young age, drawing initial inspiration from her mother. Guha's talent was later nurtured by renowned maestros such as Pandit A. Kanan and Vidushi Malabika Kanan. Despite being trained in Carnatic music in her early years, she transitioned to Hindustani music. She is noted for her melodious voice and proficiency in various ragas and talas. Sumitra Guha has performed in numerous concerts in India and abroad, earning significant recognition and accolades. Her contribution to music was honored by the Government of India with the prestigious Padma Shri award in 2021. Beyond performing, Guha is also dedicated to teaching and promoting Indian classical music. Furthermore, she has founded Sumadhur Hansadhwani, an institution in Delhi, to foster a deeper understanding and appreciation of Hindustani classical music.
sumy: Born in Kolkata, she started her musical journey at a very young age, drawing initial inspiration from her mother.

base_text: Clover Park is a popular baseball park located in Port St. Lucie, Florida. It was originally known as Thomas J. White Stadium, but was renamed Clover Park in 2020 as part of a naming rights deal with Clover Health. Since 1988, it has been the spring training home of the New York Mets, a professional baseball team based in New York. Every year, the Mets migrate south to prepare for the season in this park. base_text: Bhanu Pratap Jena is not a term but a renowned individual in the field of medical and biological research. He is recognised globally for his significant contributions to the area of cell biology. Born in India, he has gained numerous accolades worldwide. Dr. Jena is known as the founder of the 'Porosome' concept, a new cellular structure he discovered. Porosomes are nano-structures or cellular pores which act as the secretory portals in cells. Dr. Jena is also a Distinguished Professor of Physiology at Wayne State University School of Medicine in Detroit, Michigan. Throughout his career, Dr. Jena has authored and co-authored numerous publications in prestigious scientific journals. His research has provided insightful understandings about cell secretion and the pathological implications of impairment in this process. His discovery of porosomes revolutionizes our understanding of cell secretion, a fundamental process in all living cells. In addition to his academics, he also holds multiple patents.
sumy: He is recognised globally for his significant contributions to the area of cell biology.

base_text: The Lardil language is an Aboriginal language native to Australia, specifically the Mornington Island which is part of the Wellesley Islands located in the Gulf of Carpentaria, Queensland. This language is unique to the Lardil people. The language is classified as endangered due to it being spoken by a limited number of individuals, most of whom are of an older generation. Despite the decline, efforts are being made to revitalize the language. Lardil uses a complex system that includes both tone and stress. It is famous for its "avoidance speech", a unique style of language used to show respect by avoiding direct mention of certain people or subjects. The Lardil people also used the Lardil language in their 'songlines', which are a form of oral storytelling that maps out the landscape. Attempts to maintain the Lardil language include its inclusion in a bilingual education program in a local school. The language is part of the Tangkic language family, and its closest relative is the Yangkaal language. Although its number of speakers has declined, the Lardil language remains a significant part of Australia's linguistic and cultural heritage.
sumy: Lardil uses a complex system that includes both tone and stress.

base_text: The Pennsylvania Land Trust Association is a well-established nonprofit organization that promotes voluntary land conservation in Pennsylvania, USA. Their primary focus is towards the preservation and protection of the natural and historic landscapes of Pennsylvania. They work in association with local, regional, and state land trusts along with national conservancy agencies. The association helps in protecting the environment and the various wildlife habitats. Their work also includes the preservation of farming and forest lands in rural, suburban, and urban locations. They advocate for policies and provide resources that raise the quality of conservation work. They also conduct seminars and workshops to educate the community about the importance of land conservation. They strive to inspire people to care for and enjoy the outdoors, which results in safeguarding the future of the state’s natural places. Its membership comprises over 70 land trusts. The organization is considered a leader in promoting responsible and sustainable land use in Pennsylvania.
sumy: The Pennsylvania Land Trust Association is a well-established nonprofit organization that promotes voluntary land conservation in Pennsylvania, USA.

base_text: Jennifer S. H. Brown is a well-known and respected historian, specifically influential in North American history. She is particularly recognized for her work on the fur trade, women's history, and Native American history. Born in Norwich, Connecticut, in 1939, she pursued her academic studies at Pembroke College and later at the University of Wisconsin. She is best known for her scholarly research and contribution to understanding the Métis culture and history in Canada. Brown served for many years at the University of Winnipeg in the Department of History, where she was also appointed as a distinguished professor emeritus. Besides her academic work, she has authored several books on historical subjects and won numerous awards for her exceptional research contributions. Brown also played a significant role in developing oral history methodologies, valuing Indigenous peoples' oral accounts as valid historical sources. Her work in ethnohistory is revolutionary in the historical academic sphere, setting a precedent for future research. Brown remains a crucial figure in North American history, dedicating her life to the preservation and narrative of Indigenous peoples' history. Her work continues to inspire and influence other historians and the general understanding of North American and Indigenous history.
sumy: Jennifer S. H. Brown is a well-known and respected historian, specifically influential in North American history.

base_text: Ramchandra Dhondiba Bhandare is an Indian politician hailing from the Indian National Congress party. base_text: Freedom of Religion in Indonesia is a concept that guarantees every citizen the right to choose and practice their own religion. It is a constitutionally protected right, as stipulated in Indonesia's Pancasila, the state's foundational philosophy, where belief in one supreme God is emphasized. However, the government officially only recognizes six religions: Islam, Protestantism, Catholicism, Hinduism, Buddhism, and Confucianism. Followers of other religions sometimes face challenges in practicing their faith freely. Additionally, religious minorities often confront discrimination and violence. The Indonesian government has faced criticism over these issues. Still, it generally assures the liberty of religious expression. It promotes a moderate form of Islam and encourages religious harmony among its diverse population. Such harmony is maintained by ensuring that religious practices do not disturb public order and do not offend the beliefs of other religious communities. Thus, while there are controversies, the notion of religious freedom is an essential part of Indonesia's national identity.
sumy: However, the government officially only recognizes six religions: Islam, Protestantism, Catholicism, Hinduism, Buddhism, and Confucianism.

base_text: Extreme hardship is a term often used in legal contexts to refer to exceptionally challenging circumstances that an individual or family may be going through. This can include situations such as severe financial difficulty, major health issues, or extreme psychological distress that is above and beyond what a person might normally experience in life's ups and downs. It's often used in immigration law, when a person is trying to show that deportation or denial of a visa would cause extraordinary trouble for them or their family. Often, it requires clear and convincing evidence to prove the extraordinary nature of the hardship. Extreme hardship is highly subjective and depends on individual circumstances. It's not just about average difficulties or inconveniences; it involves serious adversity or suffering. For instance, a situation may be categorized as extreme hardship if it leads to substantial and long-lasting detriment to an individual's livelihood, health or welfare. Each case of extreme hardship is unique and treated distinctly based on its facts. Crucially, it's typically used in a context where relief or an exception is being sought from an otherwise applicable rule or law.
sumy: This can include situations such as severe financial difficulty, major health issues, or extreme psychological distress that is above and beyond what a person might normally experience in life's ups and downs.

base_text: Gardner Army Airfield is a term that refers to a historic military airfield located in California, United States. Specifically, it is situated in Kern County, near the city of Taft. The airfield was developed in 1941 and was initially used during World War II by the United States Army Air Forces for pilot training purposes. It was equipped with numerous aircraft including B-25 Mitchell bombers. Besides its usage for operational training, it also functioned as a detachment of the 459th Base Headquarters and Air Base Squadron. It was deactivated and declared surplus in 1945 at the end of the war. After this, it was transformed into a civil airport, Taft-Kern County Airport. While the runways are no longer visible, remnants of taxiways are still evident. Despite numerous changes, the memory of its wartime past remains intact within the Gardner Army Airfield. Today, it stands as an important reminder of U.S military history.
sumy: Specifically, it is situated in Kern County, near the city of Taft.

base_text: Nicholas Herkimer was an American military general active during the American Revolutionary War. He was born around 1728 in the German Palatine district of New York to immigrant parents, and was one of the oldest of about 14 siblings. As a young man, he got involved in the local militia and began his military career. During the Revolutionary War, he received the rank of brigadier general in the Tryon County militia, from where he led his forces against British and Indian allies. Herkimer is notably recognized for his leadership during the Battle of Oriskany in 1777. Despite being seriously wounded, he continued to direct his soldiers, which played a significant part in the strategic success of the overall Saratoga campaign. His actions made him a hero and an iconic figure in the Mohawk Valley, New York. Today, Nicholas Herkimer is remembered through several monuments and place names. His home, the Herkimer Home State Historic Site, is a museum exhibiting the life and times of this heroic figure. Herkimer tragically died from his wounds only 10 days after the Battle of Oriskany.
sumy: As a young man, he got involved in the local militia and began his military career.

base_text: Thomas Coningsby was a prominent English political figure during the late 17th and early 18th centuries. He was born in 1656 into a wealthy Herefordshire family. Coningsby served in several roles within the British government, most notably, he was appointed Lord of the Treasury in 1690, a position he held until 1694. He played a crucial part in the politics of his time, largely supporting the Whig party. base_text: The Callippic cycle is a period of time used in astronomy. It was devised by the Greek astronomer Callippus in the 4th Century BC. The purpose of this cycle is to harmonize the movements of the Sun and Moon, similar to the Metonic cycle. However, the Callippic cycle is four times the length of the Metonic cycle. The cycle lasts for 76 years, or 27,759 days. This cycle comprises of 940 lunar months. This makes it more accurate than the Metonic cycle, which lasts for 19 years. The Callippic cycle was once used to determine the dates of the Olympic Games in ancient Greece. It became less popular due to the complexity and inaccuracy over long periods. However, it still played a vital role in the history of astronomy and calendar making.
sumy: This makes it more accurate than the Metonic cycle, which lasts for 19 years.

base_text: Fluorescence intermittency in colloidal nanocrystals refers to a phenomenon where these tiny particles, despite their continuous excitation, randomly switch between periods of high and low light emission. The term "fluorescence" refers to the emission of light by a substance that has absorbed light or other electromagnetic radiation, while "intermittency" refers to the sporadic or on-off behavior. In this context, "colloidal" refers to the microscopically dispersed, yet stable, suspension of the nanocrystals in a solution. What happens is that, under constant light illumination, these nanocrystals don't emit light continuously, they blink. This blinking effect is what is referred to as fluorescence intermittency. These fluctuations or "blinking" can occur over a wide range of timescales, from microseconds to several minutes. The precise reasons for this blinking aren't fully understood yet. However, its understanding is important for applications of these nanocrystals in areas like biological imaging and optoelectronics. This phenomenon tends to limit the effectiveness of nanocrystals in these fields. Thus, research is ongoing to better understand and hopefully control fluorescence intermittency in colloidal nanocrystals.
sumy: Fluorescence intermittency in colloidal nanocrystals refers to a phenomenon where these tiny particles, despite their continuous excitation, randomly switch between periods of high and low light emission.

base_text: LGBT rights in Zambia refer to the rights and societal treatment of individuals who identify as lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender in the African country. The legal and social landscape in Zambia is profoundly hostile towards LGBT people. In this country, homosexuality is illegal and carries severe penalties that can range up to 14 years in prison. The law also doesn't protect people from discrimination based on their sexual orientation or gender identity. This harsh environment is compounded by strong societal norms and traditional values that categorically reject homosexuality. The Zambian government, religious groups, and traditional leaders all openly condemn same-sex sexual activity. Moreover, advocacy for LGBT rights is not officially recognized and activists face serious threats. Countless reports of harassment, threats, and violence against LGBT individuals have surfaced over the years. In recent years, human rights organizations have urged for acceptance and recognition of LGBT rights in Zambia. However, the country's leadership remains adamant in their stance against advancing these rights.
sumy: The law also doesn't protect people from discrimination based on their sexual orientation or gender identity.

base_text: A Transient Voltage Suppression Diode, also known as a TVS diode, is a specialized electronic component used primarily for protection of sensitive circuitry. It helps to protect against voltage spikes or transients that could otherwise damage electronic devices. It works by clamping the voltage to a safe level when it rises above a certain threshold, known as the clamping voltage. The diode remains in a stand-by or non-conducting state until the voltage goes beyond its rated limit. When this happens, the TVS diode switches to a conducting state almost instantaneously, diverting the excess voltage away from the sensitive components. Upon return to normal voltage conditions, the TVS diode reverts back to its standby state. TVS diodes are useful in protecting against fast, high-energy events like lightning strikes or electromagnetic pulses. They are commonly used in computer circuits, power supplies, and communication lines. TVS diodes can handle very high peak currents, but only for very short durations, which makes them ideal for suppressing transient voltage spikes. In essence, a TVS diode is a guardian of electronic circuits, shielding them from potentially damaging voltage spikes.
sumy: It helps to protect against voltage spikes or transients that could otherwise damage electronic devices.

base_text:
Cerianthus refers to a genus of tube-dwelling anemones in the family Cerianthidae, which is a group of aquatic invertebrates. These creatures are commonly found in marine environments, particularly in both shallow and deep waters around the world. They are characterized by their elongated bodies, which they use to create tubes in the ocean floor where they reside. These tubes are made from a mucus-like substance which hardens once exposed to water. Unlike other sea anemones, the Cerianthus are not attached to rocks or coral reefs.

Cerianthus are typically solitary and catch their prey using their stinging cells, similar to jellyfish. They feed mainly on small zooplankton. They have two whorls of tentacles, with the outer ones being longer and the inner ones being shorter and thicker, utilized for catching food. The color of Cerianthus species can vary greatly, ranging from pale to vibrant shades. Interactions with humans are relatively rare, as these creatures prefer a secluded lifestyle deep in the ocean.
sumy: Unlike other sea anemones, the Cerianthus are not attached to rocks or coral reefs.

base_text: A Statement of Assets, Liabilities, and Net Worth, often referred to as a SALN, is a document that provides a detailed snapshot of an individual's or company's financial condition at a specific point in time. It spells out all the assets that they own such as properties, cash holdings, and investments. It also tabulates all their obligations or debts, referred to as liabilities. The difference between the total assets and total liabilities represents the net worth. The net worth can be positive, meaning assets exceed liabilities, or negative, which means liabilities surpass assets. SALN is crucial in determining the financial health of a company or individual. It can be used by lenders to decide on whether to extend credit. A high net worth suggests a strong financial position, while a low or negative net worth indicates financial instability. Regular updates on SALN help in tracking financial progress over time. In some jurisdictions, public servants are required to submit their SALN to ensure transparency and prevent corruption.

base_text: Sack-Barabas syndrome, also known as Hyper IgM syndrome type 3, is a rare genetic immunodeficiency disorder. People with this condition produce abnormal amounts of a type of antibody known as Immunoglobulin M (IgM). This results in the body's inability to effectively fight off bacteria, viruses, and other pathogens, causing recurrent infections. Sack-Barabas syndrome is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning both copies of the gene in each cell have mutations. The syndrome is characterized by low levels of other immunoglobulins, such as IgG, IgA, and IgE. Symptoms vary but may include frequent respiratory or gastrointestinal tract infections and enlarged lymph nodes. Some individuals may also develop autoimmune disorders. There's currently no cure, but treatment involves managing infections and boosting the immune system, often with immunoglobulin replacement therapy. Since it's a rare condition, further research is needed to fully understand its clinical course and prognosis. Hence timely diagnosis and appropriate treatment can enhance the quality of life in affected individuals.
sumy: This results in the body's inability to effectively fight off bacteria, viruses, and other pathogens, causing recurrent infections.

base_text: Eastern Asia, according to the World Geographical Scheme for Recording Plant Distributions (WGSRPD), is a broad region defined for the purpose of categorizing and noting the growth of various plant species in different geographical areas. This broad region comprises several countries and islands all found within the Eastern part of Asia. Eastern Asia includes the nations of China, Taiwan, Korea, and Japan. Additionally, it encompasses the regions of Mongolia and the Russian Far East. Apart from the mainland, the WGSRPD’s definition of Eastern Asia also includes numerous islands such as the Sakhalin island and the Kuril Islands. These classifications help botanists and plant researchers track plant distributions and note the areas where specific plants are found. Moreover, it aids in the study of plant migration patterns, species adaptation, and the effects of climate change on vegetation. This system was developed and is maintained by the international Biodiversity Information Standards organization. In essence, the term Eastern Asia (WGSRPD) is a botanical geography term, more than it is a political or cultural division. By design, it helps in the global initiative of observing and preserving the world's plant life.

base_text: The term "Prince of Orange" refers to the title carried by the reigning monarch of the House of Orange, a noble lineage from the Netherlands. Upon the foundation of the Kingdom of the Netherlands in 1815, the title was formalized as the precursor to the Dutch monarchy. Currently, the Dutch monarch's eldest child usually holds the title. Nonetheless, it's not automatically inherited and is typically granted by the reigning monarch. Despite its French origins, the title is now inexorably linked with Dutch history, culture, and monarchy. To this day, the term embodies a significant part of the royal tradition in the Netherlands. The current holder of the title is Princess Catharina-Amalia, the elder daughter of King Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands.

base_text: Ponca is the name of a Native American tribe in the United States that originated from the areas around the Ohio River. Their traditional homelands relocated to what is now known as Nebraska and South Dakota due to forced migration during the 19th century. The Ponca tribe is known for their farming, hunting, and warrior ethos. They held spiritual beliefs centered around force of nature, with particular reverence towards the sun, moon, and thunder. Their society was traditionally organized into clans, based on bloodlines. The modern-day Ponca is divided into two federally recognized tribes: the Ponca Tribe of Nebraska and the Ponca Tribe of Oklahoma. Each operates separately with their own governing structures and services provided for their members. base_text: Lift irrigation is a method of watering crops where water is not transported by natural flow like gravity, but rather is 'lifted' by pumps or other means. The water comes from a lower level, possibly stored in a reservoir or river, and is then distributed to fields located at a higher elevation. This method is highly beneficial in areas with varying land topography or where other forms of irrigation are not effective. It's often used when the agricultural land is located in hilly or uneven terrain or when the water source is below the level of the fields. The lifted water can be further transported through canals, pipes, or even sprayed directly onto the fields. It typically requires more energy and resources than gravity-based systems. Lift irrigation is particularly important in regions where rainfall is insufficient for crop growth. Despite its high operational costs, it's crucial for ensuring constant water supply. Proper management is required to make it sustainable and energy-efficient. So, lift irrigation is a key tool to overcome geographical challenges in agriculture.
sumy: This method is highly beneficial in areas with varying land topography or where other forms of irrigation are not effective.

base_text: A cotton field refers to an agricultural parcel of land predominantly used to cultivate cotton plants, which are native to tropical and subtropical regions in the world. These fields can be found in countries with suitable climates that encompass the right combination of long sunny days, average temperatures between 60-95°F (15-35°C), and ample rainfall for growth, such as the United States, India, and China. The crop is typically sown in the spring and harvested in the autumn when the cotton bolls, or protective casings around the seeds, open up to reveal the fibrous cotton. This process transforms the fields into an expanse of white, fluffy 'balls' that somewhat resemble snow. Cotton fields represent a major component of the global textile industry. The cotton is harvested either manually or mechanically, and then undergoes a ginning process to separate the useful fibers from the seeds. The fibers are later spun into thread or yarn and used to create cotton fabric. While designing a cotton field, it is pertinent to consider crop rotation methods that can improve soil's fertility and reduce pests. Cotton farming has socio-economic significance, particularly in developing countries, but it also carries environmental consequences due to its high water and pesticide requirements.
sumy: This process transforms the fields into an expanse of white, fluffy 'balls' that somewhat resemble snow.

With a diet primarily of insects and seeds, it often forages in shrubs and trees. The Willow Tit is a cavity nester, creating its nests in rotting stumps or trees. base_text: VMware vSphere is a cloud computing virtualization platform developed by VMware Inc. This software offers a way to create, manage, and use virtual machines that are abstracted from a layer of physical hardware resources, such as storage, network, and CPU. The primary aim of the VMware vSphere is to provide infrastructure virtualization to create and manage a virtual infrastructure at both server and data center levels. It's a powerful suite that bundles all elements of commercial virtualization elements like the hypervisor and management console. Using it can significantly reduce IT complexity, increase efficiency and flexibility, and provide a more robust, resilient, and secure infrastructure. It is essentially a datacenter solution, offering enterprises the ability to consolidate workloads, automate operations, and deliver IT resources on-demand. Furthermore, it provides disaster recovery, high availability, and fault tolerance, increasing the overall stability and reliability of the IT environment. VMware vSphere uses a client-server model, with the server managing the resources while the client is used to access and administer the virtual machines. The technology enables resources to be allocated dynamically, based on demand, thereby optimizing the efficiency of the servers. It's a significant advance in managing virtualized IT environments and is widely used by businesses of all sizes.
sumy: This software offers a way to create, manage, and use virtual machines that are abstracted from a layer of physical hardware resources, such as storage, network, and CPU.

Anomobryum is a term that refers to a genus of mosses in the family Bryaceae. This type of moss can be found in various parts of the world including Eurasia, North America, and Africa. The name 'Anomobryum' is derived from ancient Greek words that mean "irregular" and "moss", referring to the sporadic and uneven arrangement of the plants.

Mosses in the Anomobryum genus are small to medium-sized, growing in dense tufts and are typically green to yellow-green in color. They grow on a wide range of substrates including soil, tree barks, and rocks. When it comes to reproduction, Anomobryum reproduces both sexually and asexually, producing spores that are dispersed by the wind. The plants have leaves which are often oval-shaped, with a curved or twisted appearance. This genus of mosses is important for ecological functions like water retention and providing habitat for insects and other small organisms. base_text:
The temporalis muscle is one of the muscles involved in jaw movement and is responsible for closing the mouth or elevation of the mandible. This fan-shaped muscle is located on the side of the skull, inside the temporal fossa - a hollow space above the ear. It originates from the floor and medial wall of the temporal fossa and the deep surface of the temporal fascia. 

The muscle fibers converge as they descend and they end in a tendon, which passes deep into the zygomatic arch, a bony arch on the skull's side. This tendon then attaches to the coronoid process of the mandible - a part of the lower jawbone. The temporalis muscle is innervated by the deep temporal nerves, branches of the mandibular nerve, which is the third branch of the trigeminal nerve.

Its main function is to pull the mandible upwards and backwards. This is distinctively involved in crushing and grinding food due its large leverage. The muscle is also responsible for holding the mandible in position at rest. Dysfunction in this muscle can result in conditions such as temporomandibular joint disorders.
sumy: The muscle fibers converge as they descend and they end in a tendon, which passes deep into the zygomatic arch, a bony arch on the skull's side.

base_text: The History of Britain (Milton) refers to a historical work by English poet and intellectual John Milton. He undertook writing this work at the request of England’s Commonwealth Council. Milton's intent was to provide a comprehensive history of Britain, tracing its story from the earliest times up to the reign of King James I. However, due to his deteriorating eyesight, he was unable to fulfill this goal, and the work only covers the period until the Norman invasion of 1066. The History of Britain (Milton) reflects Milton’s Puritan views, with a particular focus on the conflicts between monarchs and their subjects. It is considered an important historical document, but its interpretations and narrative have often been disputed. Despite its limitations, the work demonstrates Milton’s mastery of language and extensively detailed historical knowledge. It remains an influential historical text, providing an early modern perspective on Britain's past. base_text: Amory Lovins is an American physicist, environmental scientist, and writer, noted for his work in energy policy and energy conservation. He is the co-founder and Chairman Emeritus of the Rocky Mountain Institute, an independent, non-profit think-tank that promotes the efficient and sustainable use of resources. Lovins is a strong proponent of "soft energy paths", involving the use of appropriate technologies that are both sustainable and energy efficient, such as renewable energy sources. His influential works include 'Soft Energy Paths', 'Natural Capitalism', and 'Winning the Oil Endgame'. Considered an environmental visionary, Lovins' ideas challenge the notion that economic and environmental interests are inherently opposed. His work has received recognition and praise globally for advancing new energy strategies, challenging energy policies, and advocating for energy efficiency. His ideas have helped shape the concept of a green economy, emphasizing the feasibility of transitioning to renewable energy. Lovins has been awarded many honorary degrees and won numerous awards for his significant contributions to environmental science and energy policy. The term symbolizes their power to influence the public’s opinion and scrutinize authorities. The Press is protected under laws and principles that uphold freedom of speech and expression. The initiation of the free press concept came from the belief that communication and expression through various media, including printed material, is a fundamental right. It allows for a democratic exchange of ideas and information, which is vital for a functioning society. The Press also helps to hold governments and officials accountable by disseminating accurate information. However, it can be affected by factors like media concentration, government censorship, or bias. All these highlight the importance of a responsible, independent, and balanced Press.
sumy: This term isn't limited to newspapers but also covers journalists working in television, radio, and digital media.

base_text: Ralph fitzStephen refers to a historical figure originating from Norman England. His name is representative of the patronymic naming custom in which "fitz" means "son of", so Ralph fitzStephen would translate to “Ralph, the son of Stephen”. This naming pattern was commonly used among the aristocracy during the Middle Ages in England. Details of Ralph fitzStephens's life are not widely documented, and his exact dates of birth and death are unknown. What is known is that he lived during the 12th-century and was a minor figure in Anglo-Norman society. Typically, those named with the "fitz-" prefix were of some standing, often being landowners or knights. The name is sometimes found in ancient legal documents, charters, and rolls. Over time, these names have sometimes evolved to become family surnames. As a character of historical significance, Ralph fitzStephen helps us understand the social and cultural norms of the Medieval period, particularly in England.
sumy: Ralph fitzStephen refers to a historical figure originating from Norman England.

base_text: Korkoro is a term that originates from the Romany language, spoken by the Roma people, often referred to as "gypsies". It translates to "free" or "wild" in English. The term was popularized by a 2009 French film titled "Korkoro", which is centered around a Romany family during World War II. The film portrays the family's struggle for freedom and survival during a time where their culture was heavily persecuted. In the Romany community, the term may be used to describe a sense of freedom, rebelliousness, or non-conformity. It is often associated with a nomadic lifestyle, as the Roma are traditionally a nomadic people. The term reflects the rich culture and history of the Roma, encapsulating values of freedom and resistance. Korkoro is more than a word, it's a symbol of the Roma's perseverance, survival, and enduring spirit. Overall, it represents a fundamental aspect of Romany identity and traditions. In contemporary usage, it can also be an adjective that describes someone who is free-spirited or unconventional.
sumy: The term was popularized by a 2009 French film titled "Korkoro", which is centered around a Romany family during World War II.

base_text: Mason City High School is a public education institution located in Mason City, Iowa, in the United States. base_text: The Bureau of Entomology is a governmental entity focused on the scientific study of insects. This bureau was established in the United States in 1894 and was formerly part of the United States Department of Agriculture. Its purpose is to understand the role of insects in ecosystems, beneficial insects, and harmful insects that may affect agriculture, forestry, and public health. The Bureau conducts detailed research into insects' biology, behavior, and ecology. It advises on pest management strategies for farmers, landowners, and public health officials. Knowledge from this bureau aids in controlling pest insects and vectors of diseases. The Bureau of Entomology also plays a crucial role in biodiversity conservation, by studying and protecting insect species. There are now various similar institutions worldwide, following its model. However, in the US, the Bureau of Entomology has now been incorporated into other departments and services within the Department of Agriculture. Its legacy and work continue, focusing on the same critical areas of insect science and its benefits to society.
sumy: It advises on pest management strategies for farmers, landowners, and public health officials.

base_text: Bantz J. Craddock is not a term but a person, specifically a retired U.S. Army General. His military career spanned nearly 40 years, during which he rose through the ranks to high-level leadership positions. Among his most notable posts were the Commander of the United States European Command and the NATO Supreme Allied Commander in Europe. Born in 1949, Craddock graduated from West Virginia University and attended the U.S. Army Command and General Staff College. His military commissions took him around the world, from South Korea to Europe. A decorated military leader, General Craddock also served in Operation Desert Storm and in U.S. peacekeeping efforts in Bosnia. He retired from service in 2009. Post his retirement, he's involved in various corporate and non-profit initiatives related to veterans' affairs and national security.

base_text: Limburg United is a professional basketball team based in Hasselt, Limburg, Belgium. The team plays in the top tier league of Belgium called the Pro Basketball League.
